Dynamo 1.2

## Operating system

Win 10

## What did you do? 

Publish update to Dynamo Package via the Package Manager

## What did you expect to see?
An updated package adhering to the folder structure

## What did you see instead?

The folder structure is changed (the 'extra' folders dll's get copied to the bin folder (so they appear in both folders) and the XML description file gets put in extras even though it should be in the root directory, i.e. bin). 

The other annoying problem it has is wiping the node libraries property from the JSON file, so if the package is then downloaded after updating, nothing appears in the library, so I have to re-publish the package to fix it. This needs to be fixed as its been an ongoing issue now for months. 
"

title: b'Dynamo v2.0 breaks [DefaultArgument("{}")] Attribute in ZT Nodes'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

2.0

## Operating system

Win 10

## What did you do? 

Used a ZT node in Dynamo 2.0 which has a default argument using the DefaultArgument attribute.

## What did you expect to see?

An empty list as the default input

## What did you see instead?

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/36800581-c2729438-1ca7-11e8-941b-31a9e6c7ac13.png)

I assume this is caused by the seperation of lists and dictionaries in DesignScript v2.0 where curly brackets now define dictionaries and square brackets define lists.  If that is the case, what workarounds are there so users upgrading to Dynamo v2.0 and using Packages built on Dynamo builds before V2.0 don't experience this exception?
"

title: b'Surface.TrimWithEdgeLoops not working as expected'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3.2 stable

## Operating system

Windows 7

## What did you do? 

Tried to cut holes in a planar surface with a list of planar loops

## What did you expect to see?

The outer boundary being preserved and new holes being added to the surface (holes at the darker squares):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7148394/36706893-eabc737a-1ba6-11e8-8cd9-3111150dda00.png)

## What did you see instead?

the holes got patched:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7148394/36706906-f8072c00-1ba6-11e8-9380-1a3bec3c9e90.png)

Previously I could circumvent this unexpected behavior by flipping the primary surface or by reversing the loops but that doesn't seem to be the case any more :(

Here's the code from the image:

```
s1 = Rectangle.ByWidthLength(50, 50).Patch();
n = -22..22..#12;
p1 = Point.ByCoordinates(n<1>, n<2>);
pl1 = Plane.ByOriginNormal(p1, Autodesk.Vector.ByCoordinates(0, 0, 1));
r2 = Flatten(Rectangle.ByWidthLength(pl1, 1, 1));
s2 = flip ? s1.FlipNormalDirection() : s1;
s2.TrimWithEdgeLoops(reverse ? r2.Reverse() : r2);

```
Changing the geometry range doesn't seem to have any effect either. The only way I can get the desired behavior is by using the Surface.SubtractFrom method instead. However generating all the intermediate solids and iterating with all of them or unioning them is a prohibitively expensive operation.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7148394/36707135-f6fcec04-1ba7-11e8-9eb8-5f8bfaa81e89.png)

"

title: b'IronPython Distribution Method and Standard Library'
body:
b'Hi All,

I started a thread on the Discourse forum regarding some concerns I have about the  Dynamo IronPython distribution method:

https://forum.dynamobim.com/t/distribute-revit-dynamo-with-the-iron-python-standard-library

Basically boiling down to:

1) The potential breakage of IronPython within other applications, due to the Dynamo system-wide install method of IronPython 2.7.

2) Why the path to the IronPython Standard Library _should_ be hard-coded within the available scripting environments (the Dynamo Python node specifically).

Best,

Anders (entirely new user that do not mean to pop in and make a fuss)'

title: b'Point.Project effiency'
body:
b"
[Point.Project.zip](https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/files/1673166/Point.Project.zip)
## Dynamo version

1.3.1

## Operating system

Win 7

## What did you do? 
Projected points to a complex(ish) PolySurface.
See thread here: https://forum.dynamobim.com/t/point-project-slowed-down-in-revit-2018/17514 

## What did you expect to see?

A more efficient projection of points.

## What did you see instead?

The original points themselves originate in a discretization of a curve. If I project the curve to the surface first and then project the points to that resulting curve it provides a significant effiency gain. From what I've experienced the Point.Project node also ran better with Revit 2017, but haven't been able to reproduce at the moment. I'll see if I can dig something up.




"

title: b'Loadcase GetParameterValueByName not working.'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3.2.2480

## Operating system

Windows 7 Enterprise

## What did you do? 

Tried to retrieve the name of each loadcase.

## What did you expect to see?

The result of the Python Script

## What did you see instead?

The result in the string from object


Code in python:
```
import clr
clr.AddReference('ProtoGeometry')
from Autodesk.DesignScript.Geometry import *


output = list()

for i in IN[0]:
	output.append(UnwrapElement(i).Name)

title: b'Improvement suggestion: 2D lists with empty sublists triggers "Dereferencing a non-pointer" exception'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3.2

## Operating system

Win 10

## Improvement Suggestion

I found that any 'property' node will throw an exception if a 2D list is input where the sublists contain both objects and sublists that are empty. The solution is to remove the empty sublists or flatten the list, but its not immediately obvious to users and could easily be bypassed with a better implementation in Dynamos VM. 

For example, BimorphNodes Element.IntersectsElement, or Element.IntersectsSolid output lists of this strucutre to enable the user to understand if there are any clashes. If no clashes are found, empty sublists are returned to indicate 'no clashes'. If clashes are found, the sublists are populated with the clashing elements. Maintaining the data structure is very important to enable the user to ascertain where the clashes are located, so avoiding this problem via the node itself is not an option. If the output is connected to, say, Element.Solids node, the exception is thrown. If the list is flattened or the empty sublists removed, no exception is thrown and the expected behaviour is observed (nulls where the sublists are empty). 

Can this behaviour be improved as it inhibits usability and creates an unnecessary abstraction to users (this issues is not specific to BimorphNodes for the record)?

I should add, creating methods which return the desired members (say, solids) is one solution, however this then screws up the library structure and 'shifts' the problem."

title: b'Improvement: Copy Packages to local location if source location is on a network'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3.1

## Operating system

Win 10

## Improvement Suggestion

Deploying Dynamo company-wide with a centralised location on the network for packages creates well known admin problems (namely, the dll's become read-only which prevents upgrades or deletion). 

I'm finding that in large organisations, its impractical to ask all users to close down Dynamo and Revit so changes can be made to the package folder, which leaves administrators high-and-dry if someone has forgot to close down the applications before leaving the office or if package upgrades need to be performed during working hours.

I would therefore like to make a suggestion to improve this which would involve Dynamo automatically copying package files to a local location every time its launched if the packages are derived from a network location. Maybe this can be a simple property admins can set in the users Dynamo XML preferences file, so it is manually set rather than having to change the behaviour of the application wholesale and potentially introducing a new set of problems. "

title: b'Conditional Statements Not Handling True Values'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3.1 
(Haven't been able to check other versions yet.)

## Operating system

Windows 10 Enterprise

## What did you do? 

Convert strings (or other objects) to booleans with conditional statements.

title: b'AppDomain issue with Xceed.Wpf.Toolkit.dll'
body: b"So this is a little bit weird. It has to do with the Revit's AppDomain. It's been a while since I ran into this issue, but recently I have been working on a little Dynamo WPF node and I used a control from Xceed.Wpf.Toolkit. It's all hunky dory, I can debug the project, and it all works fine. Then I decide to publish my package, and drop the Xceed.Wpf.Toolkit.dll into Dynamo's package folder, only to find out that it's clashing with something that is already loaded into Revit. I went looking and it seems that Revit itself, and out of the box has this toolkit loaded into the AppDomain, hence the clashes. It's a little weird, because they have been using it as far back as 2016 and it basically means that I cannot load it into my package. Latest version of that dll is 3.2.0 while Revit rolls in with 5 year old 2.0.0. Luckily for me the control that I was using is still there, but this just reinforces the dynamo/revit appdomain issues etc. I am not sure there is a fix to that though unless we want to manage our own app domain for Dynamo only, and then route all appropriate calls through that....what do you think Mike cc: @mjkkirschner "

body:
b'If this issue is with Dynamo for Revit, please post your issue on the [Dynamo for Revit Issues page](https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/issues).

1.3.0

## Operating system

Windows 10

## What did you do? 

I am trying to upgrade from 1.3.0 to 1.3.1
I seems like Dynamo Core goes through with the upgrade but Dynamo for Revit is stuck on 1.3.0, due to a missing DynamoRevit.MSI file.   I have searched high and low for a solution for this.
I have tried to uninstall with Autodesk uninstall tool
I have tried to uninstall with Windows Uninstall tool
I have tried to uninstall with IObit Uninstaller tool

I have uninstalled all of my revit and dynamo products and reinstalling them.

I expected to be able to upgrade Dynamo.  No I cannot see dynamo in any revit products and I really need it to complete my work

'

title: b'Custom Nodes not loading'
body:
b'## Dynamo version
2.0.0.2757
## Operating system
Windows 10

## What did you do? 

Updated Dynamo version

## What did you expect to see?

Everything working well as it was

## What did you see instead?

Everytime I save any modification inside a Custom Node (or create a new one) and then close Dynamo, when I reopen it, the Custom Node is not loaded. The error message in the console is shown in the first attached image. However, these .dyf files are at the same folder as those that are still working (C:\Users\xxxxxxxx\AppData\Roaming\Dynamo\Dynamo Advance Steel\2.0\definitions).

I\xe2\x80\x99ve realized that, after the update, Custom Nodes (.dyf files) are being saved in a Json format and the older Custom Nodes were all in xml format. It seems that Dynamo is trying to read them in a xml format, but it\xe2\x80\x99s saving them in a Json format.

![screen shot 2017-10-04 at 17 25 36](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32527731/31201205-3839b94a-a934-11e7-9d97-8a7249bf8492.png)

![screen shot 2017-10-04 at 17 23 25](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32527731/31201211-3c2687e0-a934-11e7-95b7-8b12417e37eb.png)
'

title: b"Dynamo Package Manager doesn't honour file folder structure when publishing versions"
body:
b"## Dynamo version

v1.3.1

## Operating system

Win 10

## What did you do? 

Published a new version of BimorphNodes

## What did you expect to see?

My file structure honoured:
This is whats in my bin folder:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/31071870-a0fc7f5e-a75d-11e7-85bf-b2e500ae51ee.png)

....and this is what is in my extra folder:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/31071886-b11369ac-a75d-11e7-89fa-461ea4f4cac2.png)


## What did you see instead?

Once published however, my bin folder now looks like this:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/31072049-50e5fbf2-a75e-11e7-96cc-6ed3a5c89980.png)

and my extra folder:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/31072057-5b77d536-a75e-11e7-9391-15e9cece8f26.png)

Why is the Migrations XML moved to the extra folder when the primer states it must live in the root folder of the dll? 

Why is the BimorphNodes2018.dll copied to the bin folder?

It then leads to these warnings in Dynamo, if the package is used in earlier versions of Revit, which wouldn't (and shouldn't) appear if my file folder structure was honoured:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/31072221-f946be44-a75e-11e7-9d86-107c036f1496.png)

"

title: b'Improvement Request: Node Ports to be Consistent Height'
body:
b"Hi guys! Just a quick UI improvement request :)

All versions

All OSs

Node & Code Block headers of consistent height, so that when aligned to top, all wires are straight.

## What did you see instead?

![nodeheaders](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29973601/29817956-f122f5f6-8cb1-11e7-86df-b497da9449ca.JPG)

Wires are wonky; I use keyboard shortcuts to keep my definitions looking legible and any 'wonky' lines are seen as an area which requires improvement. Is there any capacity to slightly increase the header height of all Code Blocks to make them consistent with all other nodes? 

Thanks in advance!
"

title: b'[Bug] Dynamo 2.0 does not render missing ZT nodes'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

2.0 - built from source just now.

## Operating system

Windows 10

## What did you do? 

1. Loaded a ZT library
2. Placed a few nodes on canvas, connected them, etc.
3. Saved DYN file and closed Dynamo
4. Re-opened Dynamo and file
5. None of the ZT nodes (or connections) are rendered on the canvas

![workspace-zt-not-loaded](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11439624/29591751-4c8ee888-8798-11e7-97bb-de64a1e256de.png)

6. Add ZT library again using + button next to `Add-ons`
7. Nothing happens, so I close the DYN file and re-open.
8. All ZT nodes and connections are now rendered as expected.

![workspace-zt-loaded-file-reopened](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11439624/29591757-5589b8f0-8798-11e7-8fa8-8df700d7eb93.png)


Note : between the 2 Dynamo sessions, the `.DLL` file for the ZT library has not changed or moved, there's no reason why it shouldn't see it in the first place. Dynamo `1.3+` installed on same system does not exhibit this issue. 

## What did you expect to see?

All ZT nodes correctly rendered on the canvas.

## What did you see instead?

No nodes from the ZT library were present on the canvas."

title: b"[Bug] Dynamo Player won't recognise capitalised .DYN files"
body:
b"If this issue is with Dynamo for Revit, please post your issue on the [Dynamo for Revit Issues page](https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/issues).

If this issue is **not** a bug report or improvement request, please check the [Dynamo forum](https://forum.dynamobim.com/), and start a thread there to discuss your issue.

## Dynamo version

1.3.1

## Operating system

Windows 10

## What did you do? 

I tried to load in a directory of Scripts to access via Dynamo Player. The one I was looking for exists within said directory, but didn't appear in Player.

## What did you expect to see?

The script in question.

## What did you see instead?

It appears that having a file named x.DYN won't be recognised, but x.dyn will. I'm not sure how the file type is named - but I had both lower and upper case natively from the generation of scripts.

If I manually renamed the .DYN to .dyn - and refresh player, it appears. It disappears if I do it in reverse. 

Not recognised:
![not recognised](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12857357/29168869-c75c38b0-7dc8-11e7-8917-18a4e62bca01.JPG)

Recognised:

title: b'[Feature Request] Notes output for Player'
body:
b"Could we have the ability to add in a **static notes** output to Player? You can fudge this by putting in a faux string, or a faux watch node, but it's still not quite ideal. 

This would allow for users to input micro-help files into their players scripts that would help out hugely with legibility. 

![player_notes](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12857357/29162551-b2fe5f9a-7db1-11e7-9bb2-c0a3048a2044.jpg)
"

title: b"[Feature Request] Element Id's selectable in Player Output"
body:
b"The same way the Watch node allows you to select the '**Green Element Ids**' in Dynamo, could we implement this into the renamed _Watch Output_ in Player? 

Would be pretty epic to select directly from that environment and would facilitate many efficiency gains in things such as Warnings resolution. 

In the image below, the **Element Id** outputs are blue - and non-selectable. In the Dynamo environment, they will hone in on that element in Revit.

![player_element_ids](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12857357/29162359-191219d0-7db1-11e7-84c3-147f453ca6b8.jpg)

"

title: b'Geometry Working Range indiscriminately limits floating point precision causing failures where decimal places are required beyond the limit'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3.1

## Operating system

Win 10

## What did you do? 

Simple XYZ coincident test between two points, rounded to 4DP (typical approach I take with such tests regardless of which computational design tool I use to avoid floating point inaccuracies). The requirement was to use the result to establish if sets of lines overlap and remove them. 

## What did you expect to see?

For the coincidence test to return true in every valid case within the rounded precision input.

## What did you see instead?

With precision rounded, I expect every coincident result to return true. However, the test returned false in places even though the points were unquestionably coincident. I found it was caused by the Geometry Working Range. The size of the model in question is not large: 260m x 260m.

As Geometry Working Range limits the DP, any calculations are limited to the same number of DPs. Where DPs matter, like for example, when checking if two points are coincident, this feature becomes a hindrance. The major problem is this: without increasing the Geometry Working Range, Dynamo wont output the geometry. When its increased to output the geometry, the DP limitation then scuppers any workflows which depend on a predefined number of DPs. 

One solution is to make the predefined precision bigger (i.e. less DP = less accuracy = not good) and therein lies the problem. Any node that hard-codes precision will fail/function inconsistently as a result of the geometry working range (I have published a node called `Curves.RemoveDuplicates` with a hard-coded precision of 6DP - it fails to return accurate results as a consequence of the Geometry Working Range, see examples below). 

To compound the problem, any node which has a precision input (like OOTB `Point.PruneDuplicates`) will also work inconsistently, and any graphs which worked fine prior to the introduction of the Geometry Working Range feature that include such nodes, may inadvertently break once the user upgrades to newer versions which do include it...and then they have to work out its this phenomenon causing the problem! 

Hence, I regard this a quite a serious issue as it makes the use of Dynamo inconsistent and unpredictable or adds an unnecessary complication to any geometry-based node. 

cc @kronz this is the 'major' issue with Geometry Working Range I mentioned on Twitter.

FYI @radumg

**Examples:**
The following example worked without issue prior to the introduction of Geometry Working Range.

DWG import of a road. The intention is to convert the element into a floor. The requirement is to first, exatract the top faces, then get their edges and test for coincidence by testing where centre points are coincident. By virtue of the faces being derived from a valid solid entity, the only overlapping curves will be guaranteed where two of its faces touch and the outer edges never overlap, making them easy to identify. In addition, the centre points are guaranteed to be consistent as the edges are lines.

**The curves to test**
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/29005322-b7680876-7ad0-11e7-9237-b15435742980.png)


**The result after processing** 
Fails when with Geometry Working Range is set to medium (which is 4DP according to the dialog box in Dynamo) Why? Because the script is designed to only return perimeter curves if no coincident centre points are found, and we know any curve that isn't a perimeter curve will have an overlap. Hence, where 'webbing' is occurring is where the DP rounding cap prevents the correct result from being yield (The script tests XYZ coordinates and uses the Python `round()` method with a predefined DP of 6 internally to ascertain coincidence):
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/29005309-41f3b13a-7ad0-11e7-8190-81bd555efcc4.png)

**Increasing the DP within the script**
If I re-run the script this time increasing the predefined DP to 4, works as expected. The problem I have with this is in situations where tolerance is mission critical. In these cases, Dynamo cant be used due to this problem, not to mention why it isn't documented anywhere and why it even occurs in the first place:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/29005364-dfd4cc58-7ad1-11e7-9e8a-513bcd8ab1a5.png)


**Curves.RemoveDuplicates**
In another example, Curves.RemoveDuplicates uses an internal DP precision of 6 to basically capture practically any duplicate. But since this is higher than the DP cap imposed by the Geometry Working Range, it outputs inconsistent results or fails to work (it should have found 208 duplicates, but instead finds none - and no, its not a problem with the node itself!):
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/29005438-857afe06-7ad3-11e7-8b75-0b08131c1021.png)


I'm used to working without restrictions on DP and, while maybe being pedantic, I would expect this type of limitation to be clearly flagged up at the very least, especially for engineering scenarios where precision matters. "

title: b'Improvement: ToRevitType() limitation with converting Degree-1 NurbsCurves'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3.1

## Operating system

Win 10

## Improvement Suggestion

I notice that the ToRevitType() method doesn't handle Degree 1 nurbs curves. I'm currently using the workaround shown below, however, I think it is better if the ToRevitType() did this automatically:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18601851/29004767-4801056a-7ac5-11e7-95ac-4129edbefed4.png)


Workaround:
```
def CurveConversion(tLine):
	if type(tLine) == NurbsCurve and tLine.Degree == 1:
		crv = Line.CreateBound(tLine.StartPoint.ToXyz(), tLine.EndPoint.ToXyz())

	else:
		crv = tLine.ToRevitType()
	
	return crv

```"

title: b'Feature Request: Pin tool to organise wires'
body:
b"## Dynamo version
Whenever possible

## Operating system
Windows 7

## Feature

@Racel 

It would be great if Dynamo had a native 'pin' tool to help us lock wires in place. This would help create more legible graphs and avoid the problem of giant 'spaghetti' definitions.

![pins](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29973601/27949358-568f3e36-62f5-11e7-845a-d928ebb20ffe.PNG)

Currently, as a workaround I use untitled Code Blocks to pin my cables in place (as above), however this might be confusing to new users and sometimes it's not immediately obvious which code blocks are performing actions and which are just 'pins'. "

title: b'Create Project Parameter Node Does not Create Project Parameter'
body:
b"If this issue is with Dynamo for Revit, please post your issue on the [Dynamo for Revit Issues page](https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/issues).

If this issue is **not** a bug report or improvement request, please check the [Dynamo forum](https://forum.dynamobim.com/), and start a thread there to discuss your issue.

## 1.2

(Which version of Dynamo are you using? Go to Help > About if you're not sure.)

## Windows 7

(e.g. Windows 7, Windows 8.1, etc)

## Create Project Parameter

This node does not create a real project parameter. Instead it creates a floating shared parameter that is not actually published to the shared parameter file. Somehow it's both types of parameters simultaneously.

## What did you expect to see?

Expectation is that the node would create what it says that it would create: A Project Parameter. The current state prevents it from being able to be read across projects that contain similarly instantiated Project Parameters via the node. It does not appear to be working correctly and somehow maintains a dual state in the Project.

## What did you see instead?

Parameter that results appears as a Shared Parameter, but is not actually a Shared Parameter since it is not published to the loaded Shared Parameter file. 
"

title: b'Add "Append" Input to WriteText node'
body:
b'Could we get an additional Input for the Core WriteText node that would allow us to Append to a file in addition to overwriting the file?
I envision this as a simple Boolean after the filePath and text Inputs:
   filePath: string
   text: string
   **append: boolean**
Inside the node, it would simply use the "a" parameter at the file open instead of the "w" option.
default if it the input isn't wired would be false so any existing graphs would still work as is without any changes

Yes, I know this could be done in Python, but rather than have a custom node that almost duplicate a Core node it seems like this would be a simple addition to the existing Core node. 
(I hate it when people say that)
Further discussion on the DynamoBIM forum here:
https://forum.dynamobim.com/t/wish-add-append-option-to-writetext-node/12489'

title: b'Nodes as members of multiple groups'
body:
b'## Dynamo version

1.3 stable

## Operating system

Windows 7

## What did you do? 

Added a node to a group using box selection from right to left, accidentally selecting **two** groups
![before](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3014437/27174209-8fa98c76-51bb-11e7-8de7-8a7da7f3e118.PNG)

## What did you expect to see?
Apart from the fact that this happended by accident, any of the following:
* The "Add to group" command greyed out
* The "Add to group" command expanding to two options ("Group 1" & "Group 2")
* An error message like "You cannot add an item to more than one group"

## What did you see instead?
![after](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3014437/27174319-fcbd9df2-51bb-11e7-8ba9-27e0310bab97.PNG)
My observations are these:
* When in doubt, Dynamo will add items to the oldest group in the selection
* Items in other selected groups will be added to that group as well (probably only when using left-to-right selection boxes since that will also select all items contained in a selected group).

Here's a diff of the graph before and after the grouping operation:
![dyndiff](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3014437/27174521-c22a5a4e-51bc-11e7-81b6-949e40a88201.PNG)

While the ability to nest groups has been requested as a new feature (#6603), I believe this to be a bug, since in this case the individual elements are added to a second group (instead of the nested group's Guid).

CC @Racel '

title: b'Curve offset direction is inconsistent'
body:
b"The offset direction of curves (lines in particular) is not consistent with the curve's normal. Instead offsets appear to respond to their orientation relative to the world coordinate system - this is confusing and unpredictable.

This is related to this request 6585 -
but I would propose that rather than (or in addition to) a manually specified offset side, the default behavior of the function should be consistent relative to the curve direction.

Original report from @AndrewHeumann
https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/issues/1661#issuecomment-300672003
tracked internally: https://jira.autodesk.com/browse/DYN-826
"

title: b"Multiplication of large numbers doesn't work as expected"
body:
b"Please see here: https://forum.dynamobim.com/t/dynamo-calculation/11825

Basically if number is too big the Integer32 can't hold it, and it returns a weird result instead of a meaningful exception: 

MSDN reference: https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.int32.aspx

cc: @kronz 
"

title: b'Python Custom Nodes are adding additional (and unnecessary) ranks to output lists'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3

## Operating system

Win 10

## What did you do? 

Output a 1D list from a python script in a custom node

## What did you expect to see?

A 1D list of elements

## What did you see instead?

A 2D list. It seems that when a python script is wrapped in a CN, the CN adds an additional rank to the output list. If the same python script is copied and pasted into a DYN, the output behaves as expected. This isn't an isolated problem, but the second time I've experienced this problem (first time I observed this behaviour I thought it was something to do with outputting a jagged array...turns out I was wrong!).

The only way to circumvent this problem is to defy all logic and index the output list from Python in the body of the code.

**Python script in DYN** (output 1D list, as expected):
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/26100391/a5595b94-3a25-11e7-858f-367dcf59e50f.png)

...the same python script in a CN outputs this:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/26100304/614310da-3a25-11e7-9e6e-b0399b5906a1.png)

**Workaround:- Index the output list within the Custom Node:** 
I would expect this to return the first item
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/26100081/bf52d008-3a24-11e7-8755-7488f991d35f.png)

...instead, it defies all logic and returns a list! The behaviour - or the output list structure I should say - is now as expected:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/26100063/b4ec095e-3a24-11e7-9ead-d8014756ff97.png)

...copy that python script to a DYN...and the first item is returned, as expected, but obviously exhibiting different behaviour from the CN:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/26100188/1891d4b6-3a25-11e7-9bde-99e9e7f94d01.png)
"

title: b'Changing Geometry Working Range scales new Coordinate Systems incorrectly'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.3
## Operating system

Win 10

## What did you do? 

Set the Geometry Working Range to Large.

Created a `Point.ByCartesianCoordinates` (X=500 ,Y=500) and a `CoordinateSystem.ByOrigin` (XYZ, X=2000). Connected the new CoordinateSystem to the cs input of the point. 

## What did you expect to see?

The point translate using the new cs as its origin. 

## What did you see instead?

The cs position in the geometry view is 'rescaled' by 1000, whereas the point is not, resulting in an incorrect translation of the point if the new coordinate system is input. 

In the attached video you can clearly see the problem. The point is a long distance away from the coordinate system with X=500 ,Y=500, despite the fact the CoordinateSystem X = 2000 (i.e. the Point shouldn't be beyond the CoordinateSystem  along X). Notice the output of coordinates from both nodes. In addition, if the CoordinateSystem is used as the cs to the Point, it appears to translate the point from itself (as expected) but since its positioned incorrectly in the geometry view, the result must be wrong:


[Recording #84.zip](https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/files/1002418/Recording.84.zip)

![untitled-1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/26078486/a2510532-39b7-11e7-8286-cc2a2e551a57.jpg)

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/26078214/abd6ac3e-39b6-11e7-88eb-9d5e9be8206b.png)"

title: b'Json Serialization Updates for Dynamo'
body:
b'The purpose of this proposal is to define the json graph format for Dynamo graphs. This graph format splits the graph into two parts. The first part represents the topology of the graph using nodes and connectors. The second part contains objects related to the visualization of the graph. Everything not related to describing compute connectivity, or visualizing the graph, will be considered an application concern and will need to be stored elsewhere. An example of this would be `Nodes` versus `Cameras`. `Nodes` are required in the graph to describe function calls, but `Cameras` are only used by current Dynamo applications to save vector information related to the user's viewpoint when visualizing the scene in 3D.

### Motivations
- One graph definition shared between Dynamo, CoGS/TS, and AVP.
- The ability to add custom converters to serialize to property sets.
- Direct serialization of `NodeModels`. No more `Serialize()` and `Deserialize()` methods. We will be able to remove inconsistent xml serialization code. Node authors have used attributes and elements non-discriminantly over the years, resulting in bloated parsing and deserialization code. 
- Refactoring of Dynamo base classes. Properties related to visualization of the graph should live in the view model or the view.
- Move versioning from Dynamo to the graph. As more systems rely on the shared graph format, it will be necessary to have a version which means something across the entire system. It is possible that this version can also be tied to the design script language, and that bi-directional conversion between DS and the graph is a requirement.

### What Has Already Been Done
- The graph schema for CoGS. https://dev-cogs.thunderstorm.autodesk.com/computation-graph/v1/docs#operation/executeGraph
- Attribution of Existing Classes to Support Serialization to Json. https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/blob/master/src/DynamoCore/Graph/Nodes/NodeModel.cs), although it is not used as Dynamo's file format.
- Command line support for graph conversion to json.

### Additional Questions and Considerations
- Does the json graph format become Dynamo's _one_ graph format? If so, we will need to edit the proposal below to consider custom nodes.
- If `Port` descriptions are not stored in the graph, where are they stored? Is it possible to have shared function meta-data across Dynamo, AVP, CoGS, and TS.
- One source of truth for port and function descriptions. This would benefit localization.

### The Proposed Graph Format
```json
{
  "Id": "f170f3ea-ae94-43c1-af0c-e2fa76ebc725",
  "Name":"My graph",
  "Description":"A compute graph.",
  "Nodes":[
    {
      "Id":"aNode",
      "ConcreteType":"Dynamo.Graph.Nodes.ZeroTouch.DSFunction, DynamoCore",
      "NodeType":"FunctionNode",
      "FunctionSignature":"Autodesk.DesignScript.Geometry.Point.ByCoordinates@double,double,double",
      "VariableInputPorts": true,
      "Inputs":[
        {
          "Id":"aPort",
          "UseLevels":false,
          "SelectedLevel":2,
          "KeepListStructure":false
        }
      ],
      "Outputs":[],
      "Replication":"auto"
    }
  ],
  "Connectors":[
    {
      "Id": "593c497e-08e3-485a-bf5d-1943d87a9c3b",
      "Start": "38727d94-86bd-4db8-b2a3-95baa1ac8a85",
      "End": "54c0f71a-524b-4443-9972-1e433a0dceb4"
    }
  ],
  "Dependencies":[
    "b7d9beae-14a0-485b-b259-27d0861eb165",
    "e1764a07-f1f4-4257-a672-9920cd7acc4a"
  ],
  "Bindings":[],
  "View":{
    "X":0.0,
    "Y":1000.0,
    "Zoom":0.5,
    "NodeViews":[
      {
        "d65016b6-6845-4423-a831-d20cbf7d37d4":{
          "Name":"Point.ByCoordinates",
          "X":0.0,
          "Y":5.0,
          "IsVisible":"true",
          "IsUpstreamVisible":true
        }
      }
    ],
    "Cameras":[],
    "Annotations":[
      {
        "Id": "A group of nodes.",
        "Nodes": [
          "61aa6da7-0f40-4fbd-b600-05e0daf7e70c",
          "6f0d0008-b446-40aa-be41-75fb3b375f39",
          "00fdf5cf-f509-40d0-afbb-e83957b19cf3",
          "3ea93ee6-7419-4e6a-9748-25737de09ff4"
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```
### Proposed Changes

New JSON Graph Format | Current JSON Graph Format | Updates to Dynamo | Comments |
---|---|---|---|
**Graph** |
`Uuid` | `Uuid` | `Id` | The unique identifier of the graph.
`Name`| `Name` | | The user-defined name of the graph.
 | `LastModified` | Remove from serialization. | The date/time representing the last update of the graph.
 | `LastModifiedBy` | Remove from serialization. | The unique id of the last user who modified the graph.
`Description` | `Description` | | A description of the graph.
`Nodes` | `Nodes` | | An array of `Node` objects.
`Connectors` | `Connectors` | | An array of `Connector` objects.
`Dependencies` | | Add a `Dependencies field to `WorkspaceModel`. | An array of identifiers of graphs that are used as functions in this graph.
`Bindings` | `Bindings` | Change `sessionData` to `Bindings`. | An array of base-64 encoded key value pairs which relate call sites in the graph to data in an associated data store
`View` | | Adjust serialization logic to optionally serialize workspace view data. | An _optional_ object which has properties related to the visualization state of the graph
**View** | 
`X` | `X` | Move to `WorkspaceViewModel`. | The x coordinate of the upper left corner of the graph relative to the current viewing frame.
`Y` | `Y` | Move to `WorkspaceViewModel`. | The Y coordinate of the upper left corner of the graph relative to the current viewing frame.
`Zoom` | `Zoom` | Move to `WorkspaceViewModel`. | The scale factor between 0.0 and 1.0 of the graph.
`Cameras` | `Cameras` | Move to `WorkspaceViewModel`. | An array of `Camera` objects.
`Annotations` | `Annotations` | Move to `WorkspaceViewModel`. | An array of `Annotation` objects.
`NodeViews` | | Adjust serialization logic to optionally serialize node view data. | A map of objects, keyed by the node id, which contains coordinates of each node.
**NodeView**
`Name` | `DisplayName` | Change to `Name`.
`X` | `X` | Move to `NodeViewModel`.
`Y` | `Y` | Move to `NodeViewModel`.
`IsVisible` | `IsVisible` | Move to `NodeViewModel`.
`IsUpstreamVisible` | `IsUpstreamVisible` | Move to `NodeViewModel`
**Port**
`Id` | `Uuid` | | The identifier of the port. Id should be unique within the graph.
`UseLevels` | `UseLevels` | | A bool which specifies whether the `selectedLevel` and `keepListStructure` properties are considered.
`Level` | `Level` | | The level, starting from 0 at the leaf nodes, of nested data which is to be extracted at this port.
`KeepListStructure` | `ShouldKeepListStructure` | Rename to `KeepListStructure`. | `KeepListStructure` is a bool which specifies whether the incoming list topology should be maintained in the final data.
**Node**
`Id` | `Id` | | The identifier of the graph. Id should be unique within the graph.
`ConcreteType` | `ConcreteType` | | The location of the function identified by the `FunctionSignature` property. For .net assemblies used in Dynamo, this will be a fully qualified type name like `Dynamo.Graph.Nodes.ZeroTouch.DSFunction, DynamoCore`.
`NodeType` | `NodeType` | | The node type to be used on the server.
`FunctionSignature` | `FunctionSignature` | | The full qualified name of a function, including its parameters. Parameters are required to disambiguate overloaded functions.
`Inputs` | `InputPorts` | Rename to `Inputs`. |  An array of `port` objects.
`Outputs` | `OutputPorts` | Rename to `Outputs`. |  An array of `port` objects. 
`VariableInputPorts` | `VariableInputPorts` |  | A bool which indicates whether the node has a variable number of input ports.
`Replication` | `Replication` |  | Used to identify the replication strategy used by this node.
**Annotation**
`Id` | `Uuid` | |  The identifier of that annotation. `Id` should be unique within the document.
`Nodes` | `SelectedModels` | Rename to `Nodes`. | An array of unique identifiers of nodes which are referenced by this annotation.
'

title: b'Register C# node for forced execution'
body:
b"## Dynamo version
1.2.1

## Operating system
Windows 10

## What did you do? 
Made a class (singleton pattern) in a zero-touch library, which can 
- add items to (`SingletonClass.Add()`)
- update those items (`SingletonClass.Update()`)
- display all its items. (`SingletonClass.ListAll()`)

### Steps to reproduce
#### No elements in singleton class yet
![before](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11439624/24530463/f9c3acde-15a9-11e7-8330-a0f0e2d8ac08.PNG)

#### Added a new item to class's static list - `ListAll` node output should update
![added an item now](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11439624/24530472/0d15bfa2-15aa-11e7-9762-302d6b530849.PNG)

#### Add a new `ListAll` node to workspace & its output is updated
![after](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11439624/24530496/42236e88-15aa-11e7-9961-652c4a7a1543.PNG)


## What did you expect to see?
The output of the `SingletonClass.ListAll()` be updated after a node like `SingletonClass.AddItem()` has been added to Dynamo Workspace and executed.

## What did you see instead?
However, the output of the `SingletonClass.ListAll()` method only gets updated if I replace this node on the canvas or re-open the file.
This is because the node has no input (returning the value of the Singleton's static property) and therefore its refresh is not triggered & instead cached by Dynamo.


## Question 
My question is if there is any way of forcing this particular node to execute :
- whenever anything in the `Workspace` changes (is there an event I can subscribe/register to for example ?)
 - or if not, at least at a particular interval (and not have to set `.dyn` to Periodic

"

body:
b'## Dynamo version

1.2.3.592

## Operating system

Win 7

## What did you do?

All custom nodes to have list@level functionality available

CC @kronz '

title: b'Dynamo DesignScript graphs become unresponsive due to class clash with Archi-lab package'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.2.1

## Operating system

Win 10

## What did you do? 

Ran a script with approx 2k lines of Imperative DesignScript.

## What did you expect to see?

The script to execute (its been in use successfully for months)

## What did you see instead?

The graph is completely unresponsive and the cause is a clash with Archi-labs `List` class. This is what I narrowed it down to, and so I added DSCore.List to all `List` objects in my DS. It still doesn't solve the problem. My only option is to completely uninstall Arch-lab package, but its distributed across my clients office and relied upon by a number of their users so I can't use this as my solution. 

Considering these clashes cripple Dynamo graphs, the purpose of reporting this issue is to suggest a more robust approach to DesignScript libraries and third-party libraries to prevent this from happening.

If you need the example DYN to run tests, I can provide one.
"

@Racel

title: b'Excel.ReadFromFile'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.2.1.3083

## Operating system

Windows 7

## What did you do? 

I used the node Excel.ReadFromFile.

## What did you expect to see?

I expect to see the data flow into the node without Excel and the workbook opening.

## What did you see instead?

Excel and the workbook opened. That in itself is not why I'm filing this issue. The problem is that a process is being run with a switch and that switch prevents Excel from asking the user to save changes to a file if there are changes made. Here's what the process looks like in Task Manager and notice the switch at the end:

![excel](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4656191/21436519/9277b370-c844-11e6-8c93-3f9eba3aaffa.png)

The main problem is that even after closing the definition or Dynamo, this process stays running so if a user then opens an Excel file, makes changes, and clicks the X to exit, no prompt is issued to save the file, so changes WILL be lost inadvertently. I would expect the following:

- Excel would not open and perhaps only open in the background (not visible). This is possible via the API as far as I know and can be made hidden;
- Once the definition or Dynamo is closed, the process should be terminated. In my case I realized what was happening and I killed it manually, at which point a new session of Excel resumed normal operation.

Thanks. "

title: b'File.Delete and File.Copy'
body:
b'If this issue is with Dynamo for Revit, please post your issue on the [Dynamo for Revit Issues page](https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/issues).

If this issue is **not** a bug report or improvement request, please check the [Dynamo forum](https://forum.dynamobim.com/), and start a thread there to discuss your issue.

## Dynamo version

1.2.1

## Operating system

Windows 7 & Windows 10

## What did you do? 

I'm trying to understand the behavior of these nodes and perhaps make some suggestions. It appears that these work once and don't pass a result (out port is "void" and the node returns "null"). It would be valuable if these pass a result instead of null.

How can these be used in conditional situations? For example if a file exists at destination, I would like to delete it. Or if it doesn't exist, copy a new file from some source location. These nodes just take a path and I'm looking for something that triggers them to work or sit idle.

I also don't understand the order these run within a graph in relation to other nodes. Let's say I want to do the following in this order:

a) Copy an Excel template file from source to destination and give it a new name;
b) Take some data a write it to this newly named Excel file

The problem I'm running into is that the **Excel.WriteToFile** node is writing a new file before the template file has been copied and renamed, so my data goes into an empty Excel file instead. It also gives me an error because as the template file is being written with a new name, it fails since that file is already open by the Excel process which has already written data to the file and kept it open (as a side-note, it would be nice if Excel files aren't opened when read or written to, or we had control over this).

## What did you expect to see?

I'm hoping to be able to control the sequence of events as they pertain to copying, deleting and writing of/to files.

## What did you see instead?

Conflicts due to processes happening out of sequence. In a script I can control when everything happens but in Dynamo I cannot seem to have the same ability.
'

title: b'Plane.Offset strange behavior'
body:

## What did you do? 

Used Plane.Offset to translate a plane along its Normal vector

## What did you expect to see?

The offset plane with the same X and Y vectors

## What did you see instead?

Dynamo had changed the orientation of these vectors. 


DESCRIPTION:

In a Dynamo definition, we have created a Plane from its Origin and a Normal vector. This plane has then been rotated 180 degrees around its normal for better alignment with a robotic arm. But upon using Plane.Offset to create an offset copy of the rotated plane, the component outputs a Plane with the offset Origin, but its orientation is not maintained and it is reset to the axes before rotation. 

FILES:

Two files attached: the one with the problem (red highlights), and another with a workaround to get the desired outcome. 

NOTE: 

This is part of the P+W project at the BUiLD space. 

[PlaneOffset.zip](https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/files/655058/PlaneOffset.zip)
'

title: b'Node to Code unnecessarily wraps expressions'
body:
b"# Dynamo version

1.2.1.3083

## What did you do? 

N2C on 
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2978182/21188226/8f294ef0-c212-11e6-9566-396a880fbd95.png)

Results in

```
t1 = (0..10);
t2 = 1;
point1 = Point.ByCoordinates(t1, t1, t2);
```

## What did you expect to see?

```
t1 = 0..10;
pt1 = Point.ByCoordinates(t1, t1, 1);
```

There are 2 issues here:

- The 0..10 shouldn't be wrapped in () as it is the only expression in the assignment.
- The constant 1 is very short and is only used in a single location so should be constant propagated

Both of these would improve legibility. "

## What did you do?

My package never showed into Dynamo, this because the MeshToolkit dlls were loaded **after** my package dll.

As a workaround I renamed my package folder to start with a name alphabetically after the MeshToolkit folder, so that it would be loaded after it, my package finally showed into Dynamo.




'

title: b"Anonymous DesignScript Imperative block with an internal unassigned parameter doesn't throw an exception and freezes the graph"
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.2

## Operating system

Win 10

## What did you do? 

Declared a variable in an anonymous Imperative block but didn't assign any value to it.

## What did you expect to see?

For it to throw an exception, or give some warning that anonymous functions can't take external inputs.
OR
For the block to treat internal variables as new inputs then execute

## What did you see instead?

The entire graph will freeze. Nothing executes, whether in the Imperative block or other nodes on the graph. Only once the unassigned variable has an object assigned to it, does the graph start working again. The main issue is, no exception is thrown, when really it should (just like the new `@-#` and replications guides do) and this needs to be made more robust (imagine this on a big graph; everything would stop working and for the uninitiated user, it would be like trying to find a needle in a haystack!):

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/19925417/c8c840b8-a0e7-11e6-8fac-d5f3ee5df4eb.png)

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/19925430/d570874e-a0e7-11e6-9158-8ad727993fd7.png)





"

title: b'[UI] Wish: Drag and re-connect multiple wires.'
body:
b'It's quite common that I end up with a node that sprouts a whole branch of wires, connecting it to three or more other nodes. Occasionally I want to change the node or the list structure and I end up having to re-connect those three or more wires manually. In the below example I decided I want to flatten the list first and ended up having to re-connect 5 nodes spread all over the graph.

![revit_2016-10-21_14-07-03](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/19589199/75f008e2-979d-11e6-9553-7c48578ed4db.png)

It would be great if instead of doing that, I could have right-clicked (or CTRL-clicked) on the "in" output, select all five of those wires and re-connected them to the Flatten node's output in one fluid action. That would save me a whole lot of clicks, pans, zooms, etc and be a boon for overall productivity.
'

body:

Cheers! 
'

title: b'Slow Performance for Nodes with Many Inputs'
body:
b"Hi,

I've created a Domain Model for eQUEST, a building energy simulation tool, and I've wrapped this in a C# library to expose in Dynamo. Attached is an image of the graph I'm running that is taking about 5 minutes to resolve. I know from the image the nodes can't be read, but ultimately each of the sections results in a list of objects that gets passed into the very large node to the right. This large node is the main domain model and all the inputs take a list of objects and where no input is supplied the default value is null. When I simulate without this large nodes and connections the runtime drops down to 1-2 seconds. When I create a unit test in Visual Studio and increase the number of objects being passed in to 100 times what is being simulated in the graph shown, the runtime is also just a couple of seconds.

Is there something related to Dynamo where runtime increases significantly with the number of inputs to a node? 

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15233892/18933643/9b9fce6c-858a-11e6-9ebd-ab60a30b23d4.png)

Sorry for posting here, but I typically find the forum somewhat unresponsive to programming questions.
"

title: b'Custom Node inputs change order or are removed without honouring connected nodes'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.2.0.2654
## Operating system

Win 10
## What did you do?

Built a custom node and removed or replaced the `Input`nodes. 
## What did you expect to see?

**When removing input nodes**
That any node(s) connected to the CN, honour (associate with) their input, and any node(s) connected to the input argument(s) that are removed get automatically disconnected

**When replacing input nodes**
Firstly, its worth stating that the inputs to the CN package are generated by the order that the `Input`nodes were created in the CN's graph.

I therefore expect to see any nodes connected to the CN honour (associate with) their input and automatically move should the CNs input shift due to the behaviour described above. 
## What did you see instead?

**When removing input nodes**
The nodes connected to the CN remain static and whichever node was connected to the final input gets disconnected - basically there is no association with the nodes connected and their input to the CN.

**When replacing input nodes**
Any nodes connected to the CN remain static, while the CN's inputs shift. This obviously throws an exception as datatypes invariably change, or if that doesn't happen, the output is erroneous as the inputs have unwittingly changed.

This animation shows the problem of replacing an `Input`node in the CN. If the `Input`node is deleted, the same behaviour is experienced, only that the node connected into the last input of the CN is disconnected:
![custom-node-input-changes](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/18834797/c8430d40-83ef-11e6-9654-a2ea875a7da3.gif)
"

title: b'Improvement: Rectangle and Polygon library confuses users'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.1.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## Improvement Suggestion:

The Polygon and Rectangle library confuses users and I would like to suggest that they are consolidated. 

Here's a typical workflow which is inconsistent: 
1. Expand Rectangle library
2. Create a Rectangle by Plane, Width, Length
3. [user needs to extract corner points], so they navigate to the Action nodes under Rectangle...nothing
Instead, they have to be conscious that Rectangle and Polygons are essentially the same thing, so:
4. Expand Polygon library, and use `Polygon.Corners`

As the above example illustrates, the workflow is protracted and not necessarily obvious where really these actions are all related. Can the two libraries be consolidated?

title: b'Point.Projection partial failure. No exception warnings or nulls'
body:
b'## Dynamo version

1.1.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## What did you do?

Ambition was to import an object representing a road in DWG format (into Revit) and recreate using a floor then edit its points to create the required undulation. Workflow:
1. Import the DWG solid object
2. Extract faces (surfaces)
3. Extract boundary curves from surfaces, then extract Start/End points
4. Prune duplicates
5. Project points to XYPlane = PARTIAL FAILURE
## What did you expect to see?

All the points projected to the plane
## What did you see instead?

Majority of points projected. Some failed for reasons unknown. There are no warnings and no nulls:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/17271197/8b4481ee-566d-11e6-876e-8826d8251277.png)

I tried changing the lacing (kind of pointless as plane is a single object) scaling the plane, and also the vector since Dynamo has had issues with normalised vectors in the past (#6644). I also tried creating Line.ByStartPointDirectionLength (all lines successfully create), then use Geometry.Intersect as a workaround. Still fails the same points. I also isolated one of the problem points and tried projecting it, but...fails. Bug, or am I missing something? (Before the question of working limits is raised, its not an issue, the object is approx 100m long and in the centre of the Revit project)
'

title: b'DYNAMO OVERWRITES DYF FILES TO EARLIER, UNSAVED STATES UPON CRASHING'
body:
b"## Dynamo version 1.0.0.1180
## Operating system Windows 7 SP1
## What did you do?

Dynamo crashed (upon placing SunSettings.Current node, though I don't suspect the particulars of the crash matter)
## What did you expect to see?

My *.dyf files unchanged.

All *.dyf files have reverted to prior, unsaved states. Most of my most recently saved states are lost. The prior, unsaved states appear to be almost random per node - basically all *.dyf files now represent a moment where I was in the process of editing them, but none of these moments correspond with an actual save action. This is honestly one of the weirdest Dynamo bugs yet. It's worth mentioning that this behavior has also occurred with @AndrewHeumann

title: b'Help voor package developers?'
body:
b'When you want to start a new issue it shows:

title: b"Dynamo Null Handling - Custom Nodes comparable to GH's Sift and Recombine Workflow"
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.0.0.276
## Operating system

Windows 7 Enterprise
## What did you do?

I have attempted to create a workflow similar to GH's Sift and Recombine.  I've created a pair of custom nodes call List.Pull and List.Put that extract items from a list using an input mask.  List.Pull inserts nulls to maintain original indexing.  I am running into problems since many Dynamo nodes don't seem to like nulls -- they won't run if any portion of an input list contains a null.
## What did you expect to see?

An output list with: executed nodes on indices that DID NOT contain null items, and nulls for items with input indices that DID have nulls.
## What did you see instead?

If input list contained any nulls at all, most nodes (in attached case Geometry.Scale) are not executing any portion of the list.
[List_Replace_Non_Sequential_Items.zip](https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/files/346560/List_Replace_Non_Sequential_Items.zip)
"

body:

## Operating system

Windows 10 and 7

It would be better that there is a setting to run whole node every time.

Thank and regards,
Yoji Takahashi
"

title: b'Improvement Request_Have SaveAs dialog when downloading Packages'
body:
b"Hi,

I was wondering whether there could be an option where we could choose which location to save the packages if more than one package path exists? Since we have a network location as the primary package location and C drive as secondary when downloading a package, some users may want packages but we don't want the network package location getting cluttered and prefer this to go to their local. I know that this may result in broken scripts if not everybody has the package it originated from installed, but that's easy to remedy.

cheers,
Dan
"

title: b"Improvement: All sweep methods using a profile and path are limited and need an 'up' direction input "
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.0.1.1421
## Operating system

Win 10
## Improvement Suggestion

I am finding the BySweep methods that use a path and profile, whether from the Curve, Surface or Solid category, very limited and really needing an additional 'up' direction to improve their functionality. 

For example, I am sweeping an ellipse profile along a path curve to create a handrail, but the profile rotates 90 degrees along the length of the path and there is no way to control it. If there was an optional 'up' vector which could constrain the profile along the Z axis while using the normals of the curve to calculate the X and Y then this wouldn't be an issue. 

In the example below, the profile rotates 90 degrees along the length of the path curve using the Surface.BySweep node. The same behaviour occurs using the Solid.BySweep and Curve.SweepAsSolid nodes:

![capture](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15808292/132f0296-2b6c-11e6-9d72-e9880a06c836.JPG)
"

title: b'Improvement: Show node label name'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.0.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## Improvement Suggestion

It would be extremely helpful if the nodes can show their method names separate to the name of the node itself. On large graphs, its borderline insane not to rename nodes to something more meaningful (loosely related to #6510), and therein lies the problem. Once the node is renamed, its pretty frustrating to have to hover the mouse cursor over the node to see the information pop-up to discover what it is. What would be really useful and improve productivity, is if the node could display not only a name but also a secondary heading which only shows its method. To further extend this functionality, it could also be a global control in the View menu > _Show node labels_. If users want to retain the current appearance and not show the method name this setting simply hides the heading for all nodes.

Here's another example which illustrates the problem, a recent post on the Dynamo forum, where I'd renamed a node for graph legibility and no one can work out what they are (the two nodes in question were actually the `Point.ByCylindricalCoordinates` and `List.DropItems` for the four ptCorner nodes, positioned right on the image below):
![forum problem pres](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15807618/a0572bec-2b5a-11e6-902b-a90fbaf351e9.JPG)

What I would like to see: 

![menu example](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15807592/1b8153fc-2b5a-11e6-9829-09a075153962.jpg)

![upgrade to node name title](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15807602/470175c0-2b5a-11e6-8cc6-4c81a0277bf3.jpg)
"

title: b"Improvement: right-click 'Quick' Search should show location of node in the Library"
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.0.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## Improvement Suggestion

It would be very useful when using the right-click search menu to show either information of where the required node is located in the Library or for new functionality to be added which will automatically expand and highlight the required node in the library. (To clarify what is meant by 'the required node' it is whichever node listed in the search results the user has placed their cursor over).

This request has also been made by a number of new users who I'm teaching Dynamo.

One example is the Flatten node. There are two flavours and both are located in different categories in the Library. One is located in CORE > List > Flatten the other is in BUILTIN > Flatten. While the search results for the search term 'flatten' will list both nodes, there is nothing to tell the user where either node is located in the Library. This example highlights how the search tool could be improved as its current usage effectively divorces the user from the typical interactions of Library to graph.

This is especially problematic for those who want to grasp a better understanding of the Library. The search tool, while very useful, hinders any such endeavour. 

![capture](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15650414/4bedcfbe-2670-11e6-95e8-3e4d032d3787.JPG)
"

title: b'Excel.WriteToFile node corrupts formulae in referencing worksheets'
body:
b'## Dynamo version

1.0.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## What did you do?

Write data from Dynamo to an Excel (v2007) workbook. The Excel is a template which has two sheets: a data dump from Dynamo and sheet which processes the incoming data using ordinary Excel formulas.
## What did you expect to see?

Any new data being copied to the Excel from Dynamo to be processed by the formulas set up in the second worksheet
## What did you see instead?

Dynamo appears to corrupt all of the formulas in the second worksheet as they report #REF! once the incoming data is overwritten in the first worksheet. It appears that Dynamo is deleting and recreating the worksheet instead of simply writing to it. See images for example workflow and problem:

**Workflow**
**1. Create the graph and write some data to Excel worksheet:**
![update data to excel dynamo](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15504738/4e86619e-21b8-11e6-940d-7cd15f6f3b0c.JPG)

**2.In the second worksheet write some formulas to process the incoming data from the first worksheet:** 
![process data using formulas in sheet2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15504668/fb990d4c-21b7-11e6-9d80-48c106208831.JPG)

**3. Update Dynamo and write the new data back to Excel:**
![write data to excel dynamo](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15504667/fb985244-21b7-11e6-9936-bce384abf0b4.JPG)
**4. The formulas in the second worksheet are now corrupted:**
![corrupts formulae](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15504772/7a05ed44-21b8-11e6-8154-ecc363f38dd5.JPG)

title: b'Arc.ByStartPointEndPointStartTangent fails using a normalised vector'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.0.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## What did you do?

Created an arc using the Arc.ByStartPointEndPointStartTangent. The tangent start vector was derived from an adjoining arc with the intention to create a tangency.
## What did you expect to see?

The new arc tangent to the arc from which the start vector was derived.
## What did you see instead?

The node failed and displayed the following warning:

> Could not create the plane! The desired axes of this plane are parallel. 

However, it seems this error is caused by a tolerance issue. As the vector is normalised (i.e. length of 1), I found if the same vector is rebuilt but increased in length, then the node works as expected. Oddly, if the vector length is less than 8.3 then the node fails. I'm working in mm and the radius of the arcs in question are 7500mm.

 **Arc.ByStartPointEndPointStartTangent Node fails using a normalised vector:**
![arc bystartpointendpointstarttangent fails with normalised vector](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15342869/73db9ee6-1c90-11e6-9957-fe35d60ee1c2.jpg)

 **Arc.ByStartPointEndPointStartTangent Node works if the same vector is rebuilt:**
![arc bystartpointendpointstarttangent works when vector is rebuilt](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15342953/007d27a2-1c91-11e6-9e85-ee245aaea242.jpg)
"

title: b'Improvement: Shift- and Ctrl- window select to add/remove nodes from selection'
body: b'Currently (as of 1.0.1.1157), Dynamo supports adding one node at a time to the current selection while shift is held down. However, it is impossible to modify your selection otherwise - you cannot use ctrl (or shift or alt or anything) to _remove_ an item from the selection, and you definitely cannot add multiple items to a selection by holding down shift and performing multiple window selects. This seems like a UI no-brainer. \n'

title: b"Improvement: Node 'Show Label' settings UI improvements"
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.0.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## Improvement Suggestion

The Show Labels setting is pretty useful to visualise data structure - I'm finding with new users its invaluable. However, there are also some improvements that would aid usability:
1. On even average sized graphs it becomes difficult to decipher which node the displaying labels are emanating from. This is a big problem when all you want to do is switch them off! An icon or some other marker on the nodes to indicate that the labels of the node are active would be a big aid. 
2. A setting in the Edit menu (or right-click quick menu) which can globally set any active Show Label setting to off
3. Colour - designers are, by nature, visual so colour coding nodes when their state changes is very helpful. If the icon/marker suggestion is too discreet, nodes which change colour would be very helpful 

Take this graph - not very big or complex, yet its very easy to lose track of the nodes that have their labels switched on:
![show labels](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15323344/7c3a3c02-1c39-11e6-9f47-0ad71753b670.JPG)
"

title: b'Static methods fail in Imperative DesignScript code'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.0.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## What did you do?

Used a static method Curve.PointAtParameter() to put a point on a list of curves in an imperative DesignScript def. I used a for loop to iterate a collection of closed curves.
## What did you expect to see?

A point at the specified parameter on each of the curves iterated by the loop
## What did you see instead?

nulls.

Using the same static method in a code block works as expected. Using the same method non-static works in imperative code. I suspect this behaviour is 'by design', but I would expect to use either paradigm without limits. If that is the case, this behaviour is also not good for new users looking to develop coding skills as IMHO its too abstract and perhaps should be improved/simplified/more flexible/more concise etc, etc, etc - it is supposed to be a scripting language after all.

![static methods fail in designscript](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15229747/5a4ad776-188a-11e6-930a-38f906fdcbf5.JPG)
"

title: b"Improvement: 'helper' inputs for closed curves using Curve.PointsAtEqualChordLength or Curve.PointsAtEqualSegmentLength"
body:
b'## Dynamo version

1.0.0
## Operating system

Win 10
## Improvement Suggestion

The Curve.PointsAtEqualChordLength or Curve.PointsAtEqualSegmentLength nodes need a big improvement to deal with closed curves. 

I expect to see points arrayed equally between the curves parameter (t) space. Instead, both nodes place points one division before the end of the curve, leaving a big gaping gap in an otherwise perfect array! 

I think what would work really well would be two new boolean inputs for both nodes: includeStartPoint and includeEndPoint. The user can then decided which to keep or discard, especially where the overlap will occur at the start/end of the closed curve.

![curve pointsatequalchordlength or curve pointsatequalchordlength](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/15162758/87deecca-16fc-11e6-8656-5347540398da.jpg)
'

title: b'Geometry.Split breaks up polysurfaces into constituent surfaces making the results unusable'
body:
b'If this issue is with Dynamo for Revit, please post your issue on the [Dynamo for Revit Issues page](https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/issues).

If this issue is **not** a bug report or improvement request, please check the [Dynamo forum](http://dynamobim.org/forums/forum/dyn/), and start a thread there to discuss your issue.
## Dynamo version

1.0
## Operating system

Windows 7
## What did you do?

![splitproblem](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6430819/15086673/5da337f8-13b0-11e6-930f-74fea14273fa.png)

1 polysurface contains 3 surfaces.
A single line is used to split the single polysurface, and the Geometry.Split command returns 6 surfaces.
## What did you expect to see?

2 polysurfaces, each containing 3 surfaces.
## What did you see instead?

6 individual surfaces.

The problem is that the current behavior of the Geometry.Split node makes it nearly unusable with polysurfaces.  There is no algorithmic workaround to stitch the polysurfaces back together once the information has been lost about which constituent surfaces belonged with which other constituent surfaces.
'

title: b'Improvement: Inconsistent input names for List methods'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

1.0.1
## Operating system

Win 10
## Improvement Suggestion

There is a minor improvement I would like to suggest for the naming of the inputs for some of the List methods. You will see in the image that the `List.Create`node and `List.Join` node expects 'List0', 'List1', etc. As list indexing always starts from 0, this nomenclature goes without saying. However, for the other nodes I've included in the graph, they name the inputs with 'List1', 'List2', etc. While this isn't really an issue, its worth mentioning as a new user I was introducing to Dynamo and data structures found this quite odd (having been told all list, regardless of rank, start from index 0), and I have to concur. Any chance the naming of such inputs can be made consistent across the board?

![capture](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/14941805/dd57ec00-0fa0-11e6-9b8c-ab0ed5ef3f2d.png)
"

title: b'Improvement (and possible bug): Number node and Integer node'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

0.9.2
## Operating system

Win 10
## What did you do?

Number node object type registering as an int not a double. This causes equality errors when evaluating, for example, a list of doubles against the number node.

See #6529 for further details and an example
## What did you expect to see?

I expect a double from the number node. It's object classification is int32
## What did you see instead?

Equality using a number node fails when evaluating for equality against a double
## Improvement suggestion

Dynamo should have a number node AND an integer node, just like sliders. This, I expect, would resolve the issue reported in #6529 
"

title: b'List.AllIndiciesOf inconsistent behaviour with number node and output from Vector.Dot list'
body:
b'## Dynamo version

0.9.2
## Operating system

Win 10
## What did you do?

Output the dot product of two vectors (results are in a list). I want to identify all the co-linear and opposing test vector results (i.e. scalars of +1 or -1) and used the Number node and List.AllIndicesOf node to return all the indexes in the list that have a value (a dot) of 1.0 or -1.0. 
## What did you expect to see?

I expect to see all the indices where 1.0 and -1.0 occur
## What did you see instead?

An empty list. 
## It gets complicated

I found that if a code block with 1.0 and -1.0 is used instead of number nodes, the List.AllIndicesOf node works as expected. Furthermore, if the output of the dot array is, instead, replaced with a list hardcoded from a code block, then the List.AllIndicesOf node works with the number nodes? Very confusing. See attached image for all three examples. 

I discovered this problem after extracting all faces from a Revit mass and using their normals to identify verticality.

![capture](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/14826271/05d24222-0bd5-11e6-978f-628afd3ed467.png)

title: b'Improvement: Dockable Text Editor and Find/Replace'
body: b'## Dynamo version 0.9.2 ## Operating system Win 10 ## Improvement Suggestion I'm finding coding using DeisgnScript quite tedious when I have written lots of code (see image for an example). The code block cant be resized, and when I zoom in to see my code, the scroll bar is out of view...so I have to zoom out, move it, zoom back in. Its very disruptive when coding and problem solving. I end up simply selecting the text to nudge the view across to avoid this behaviour. The other issue is simply finding the right block of code to do updates or troubleshoot definitions...where is it...more zooming in and out. No find tool. Its arduous to say the least. My suggestion is to have a dockable text editor panel which is capable of 'collecting' all the DesignScript defs. Should then be easy to implement a find/replace tool. Anonymous code blocks can remain put to avoid 'muddying' the text editor. '

title: b'Dot product returning erronous scalars?'
body:
b"## Dynamo version

0.9.2
## Operating system

Win 10
## What did you do?

Get the dot product of two vectors. Evaluating against world Z Vector. 
## What did you expect to see?

Dot product returned as a scalar between -1 to +1. 
## What did you see instead?

Due to the way I've created the vector for evaluation (flowing a PointByParameter on a circle with its centre point as its start point. The vector has been normalised) if I set the parameter on curve to 1 (effectively a 360 degree rotation) it returns -2.44929359829471e-16. I would also expect to see a scalar of 0!

Similarly for a parameter of 0.5 (effectively a -90 degree rotation) it returns a scalar of 1.22464679914735e-16. I would expect to see a scalar of 0! 

If I set the point by parameter to 0 (so +90 degree rotation) I get the result I expect = 0. Similarly for collinear vectors it correctly outputs +1 and opposing correctly outputs -1.

![dot product at 0deg full 360 deg rotation](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/14725447/e2337738-0813-11e6-9af8-737360f0033e.png)
![dot product at 0deg](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/14725448/e2353f96-0813-11e6-975b-fc89e299efdb.png)
![dot product at 90deg](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/14725449/e23613a8-0813-11e6-8ca7-3bb39ff99243.png)
![dot product at 180deg](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/14725451/e23b2be0-0813-11e6-8ca1-f44dfe6a22f6.png)
![dot product at minus 90deg](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18601851/14725450/e23a3262-0813-11e6-8c0d-6f20fd588139.png)
"

title: b'Element.Geometry inconsistency'
body:
b'Using 0.9.2.  I have lately noticed many elements that are not working with Element.Geometry.  Attached is a file containing 3 elements.  Only one of the 3 (the rectangular beam) will work with element.geometry in Dynamo.  If the rectangular beam is connected and joined to the elliptical column, it will not work with element.geometry.

I have looked at all 3 elements using RevitLookup.  For the Rectangular beam, the geometry only shows "Solid".  For the Ellipse Column it shows "GeometryInstance" and "Solid". For the cable loop it only shows "GeometryInstance".

I am wondering 
1. Why won't all 3 elements work with Element.Geometry (can the node perhaps be fixed to work for all 3?)
2. if there is some issue on the way the families are built to make it work with Element.Geometry - should that be documented so that people know best practices to make their elements work with Dynamo?
3. Is there an issue with nested (non-shared) families working with Element.Geometry?  (A Generic Model nested into an empty Structural Framing family perhaps??)

[Element Geometry fails.zip](https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/files/209231/Element.Geometry.fails.zip)
'

title: b'Data Structure \xe2\x80\x94 Dynamo tends to wipe out the first empty list/null value?'
body:
b'Dynamo 0.9.1.4062  Windows 7 

Hi, I was trying to get intersection between several items by using List.Map, for example: I have 2 horizontal surface and 3 vertical surface, the data structure I\xe2\x80\x99m expecting would be {[(0,0)(0,1)(0,2)][(1,0)(1,1)(1,2)]}. 

However, if the first surface failed to intersect with other 3 surfaces, I\xe2\x80\x99m only getting {[(1,0)(1,1)(1,2)]}, and if the second one failed to intersect, I\xe2\x80\x99m still getting{[(1,0)(1,1)(1,2)][EmptyList, EmptyList, EmptyList]}, which is correct. For me, it feels like dynamo tends to wipe out the empty list/null value at the beginning until the note can successfully get some results. This can be very tricky and important to keep data structure same for future use. Any thought?

![dynamo datastructure - empty list as 1st item - test](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/10234287/14284076/fc8b6206-fb13-11e5-86ea-dbb59a051c05.JPG)
'
