title: b'Dynamo auto-assigning '
body:
b"## Dynamo version

0.9.2.4472
## Operating system

Windows 7 Enterprise Service Pack 1
## What did you do?

Opened a Project and associated Dynamo graph.

The graph had empty Family Type drop-down lists connected to an authoring node (FamilyInstance.ByPointAndLevel).

When I then opened a Revit Family (with the intention to load it into the the Revit project linked to the Dynamo graph), all of my empty Family Type nodes selected the first available family in the list, thus writing arbitrary family types into the project which caused Revit to crash.

I'm not sure why opening a Revit file would trigger a change in a Dynamo graph, especially when the two are not linked in any way.
## What did you expect to see?

If a Family Type Node is empty, it should remain empty, and not arbitrarily select a family from my project.
## What did you see instead?

Dynamo making arbitrary changes to my graph (the drop-down selection in the Family Types node) which is extremely dangerous, particularly when I'm running in Automatic mode.

![dynissue092](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6502496/14049779/cd393368-f28d-11e5-8eab-acddfe77a1ff.jpg)
"

title: b'Crash from Element.GetParameterValueByName'
body:
b'## Dynamo version

0.9.1
## Operating system

Windows 7-64 SP1
## What did you do?

My graph selects all Doors in a project, then gets the nearby Rooms
Next it compares the Door Number to both Room Numbers and sets a flag if the Door matches one of the Rooms or false if it matches neither.
## What did you expect to see?

This has worked on small projects, but on a large project with
I got an error:
**Internal error: please report: 
Dereferencing a non-pointer (3f47aacd)**
(Image attached)
This was in an Element.GetParameterValueByName node

I've attached the graph and an image of the error, but the Revit project is 400 Meg, 
If you want to test the graph, you'll also want to remove the "Filter Superdoors" node.
That node uses a parameter that is unique to our doors. 
"Normal" doors will work fine bypassing that node.
![dynamoerror](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18071127/14045134/71095028-f265-11e5-87ef-7b2149ce1ff3.PNG)

[DoorNumberQA.dyn.txt](https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/files/189557/DoorNumberQA.dyn.txt)
'

title: b'Wish: Better documentation abilities'
body:
b'I have been investigating ways to use Dynamo in our MEP group.  One thing that has struck me is that there seems to be no easy way to document what you have done, basically just codeblocks with commented out text.  The coloured groups are great but I think it would be great if you had a comment block that could be attached to a node or group that had a description of the intended behavior.  Basically so other members of your team, or any one who downloads your files can see the reasoning.

Additionally, the python nodes seem like they would benefit from being able to rename the input and output ports visible in the UI for ease of use.  Also renaming the python node while retaining a clear indication it is a python node.
'

title: b'PolyCurve.Offset not working'
body:
b'PolyCurve.Offset not working as intended.

If rectangle fed in, regardless of extendCircular input, fillets are generated, not larger rectangles.

If a series of arcs joined together into a closed polycurve are fed in, an error appears:

"Warning: PolyCurve.Offset operation failed. Unable to compute edge from curve : IG_CURVE_NON_G0 -- Curve is G0 discontinuous"

This means there is no way to accurately offset geometry, particularly when you can't define which side to offset. Offset with point as a reference would be much more useful.
'

title: b'0.91RC (and earlier versions) "Geometry.ExportToSAT" size issues.'
body:
b'I've been observing some strange behavior with the "Geometry.ExportToSAT" node. First of all, when lacing is set to shortest and you feed in  a list of geometries and a list of paths, the entire list of geometries gets exported over and over for each file path, effectively merging the list of goemetries into a single entity. The expected result is to have each individual geometry paired up with each individual path:

![dynamosandbox_2016-02-17_22-14-41](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/13112689/dcd50808-d5c6-11e5-95ca-5d4d2e0b5de7.png)

![explorer_2016-02-17_22-14-34](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/13112692/e15db848-d5c6-11e5-8597-4e83b819078b.png)

Setting the lacing to longest fixes this but it's still an unexpected result.

The bigger issue I'm having however, is that the exported file size varies a lot with the scale of the object.
![dynamosandbox_2016-02-17_22-11-38](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/13112763/3a7bf516-d5c7-11e5-8d5c-e262ab50bb9f.png)

![explorer_2016-02-17_22-11-10](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/13112766/3ee9fad0-d5c7-11e5-990c-509310dd59eb.png)

In the above example, the file size increases only 4 times. In other cases (sometimes with a simpler geometry, sometimes with a more complicated one), I've seen the size increase 8-10 times with relatively minor changes to the scale of the object.

I thought the problem might be coming from the use of the "Geometry.Scale" node, so I decided to bypass it and got somewhat similar results:

![dynamosandbox_2016-02-17_22-32-14](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/13112941/cf54ab56-d5c7-11e5-81f3-18a2a9bb3dd3.png)

![explorer_2016-02-17_22-32-47](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/13112944/d6a09aaa-d5c7-11e5-9a7f-951906b04c3d.png)

Any idea why this is happening? Can you suggest any ways to bypass this increase in size? Is there a way to have a finer grained control over the size of the file? (something like a quality setting)

When I import these ballooned files in Revit, the project's file is increased even further than the total size of tha SAT.

P.S.
As a side note, the "PolyCurve.Fillet" node's "rightSide" input seems to change sporadically with the scale of the object too. I've got no idea what this setting does, but it'd be awesome if you could somehow eliminate it. (for example evaluate the number of segments in the resulting curve; the output's curve count should always be greater then the input's )

@kronz I guess this is another issue for the ASM bucket.
'

title: b'Disable the auto-show of node output preview'
body:
b'Hi,
This is wrt the new feature in 0.9 which auto-shows the output preview of nodes when mouse enter them.

Can there be a check-menu item in the settings to enable or disable this feature? I prefer to have it the way it used to be prior to 0.9-- where I click a button to show content. This is due to two reasons in current implementation:
1-Hinders Visibility: Auto-show also means auto-hide other parts in the graph. This makes things harder to work with because they continuously get hidden as mouse travel over the graph. 
2-Performance. Sometimes, Dynamo gets very occupied with trying to "animate" the expansion of output preview lists. The software sometimes hangs, or just becomes too slow and usable. For example, if the mouse happened to have hovered over 3 nodes, it could take up to 30 seconds until the animation is done and dynamo becomes usable again. Other times, I just have to restart Dynamo. This can happen on files with under 10 nodes. I haven't identified the procedure that can reproduce this yet, but it happened a few times already upon using 0.9 in the first week. 

I am running dynamo on a fairly advanced machine with all drivers are up to date. So I don't think it is a hardware issue at all.

I realize 0.9 is in development still, but it would be great if users are given a choice of defining what becomes a default (automatic) behavior and what does not. Please consider a check-menu item in settings! :)
'

title: b'Import SAT file with "Show Edges" locks up Dynamo background thread'
body:
b"Steps to reproduce:
1. Launch Dynamo Sandbox (or in Revit, doesn't matter)
2. Set Settings > Show Edges to true
3. Create a new Dynamo script and try to import the surface from [Surface.zip](https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/files/121773/Surface.zip) (inside the .zip)
Observe that, while you can continue interacting with the Dynamo UI, the geometry never shows up, the DynamoSandbox thread is spinning (when viewed in Windows Task Manager), and if you try to close Dynamo, it hangs until you force close the program (using task manager).

Now, if you skip step #2 above (that is, set Show Edges to false), everything works as expected (the geometry is displayed immediately).

This is occurring for me on Dynamo v0.9.0.3067

Also, this appears to be the same behavior as reported in #2974, although in that case, it seems to crash regardless of Show Edges setting, so perhaps a different issue?
"

title: b'Dynamo 0.91 UI suggestions'
body:
b"First of all, I really like the direction in which 0.91 is going. A ton of things have been changed and added to greatly improve usability. 
However some of the UI changes seem to have been implemented only partially. I was waiting to see if the stable build would develop things further and now with the RC out, I have a few small suggestions:

![revit_2016-01-24_10-43-08](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/12534318/0d69826a-c28e-11e5-92ca-6eaa1dc15c3a.png)
- The watch node:
  - Why does it need a node preview toggle? Are there any plans to remove it in the following releases?
  -  It would be a good idea to make the element Ids pop out and look more like buttons, so that people know they can be selected to zoom to the element inside the Revit UI.
  - You might need to change the colour of the text inside the watch node to make it more contrasting to the background.
  - Making the watch node expandable seems to be a popular request.
- Generic Nodes:
  - With the preview toggle moved outside of the node, we're left with quite a lot of empty space at the base of the node.
  - Are there any plans to make the lacing switch a floating toggle? (Similar to the preview toggle).
  - If not, I suggest moving it to the centre of the node to make it a predominant part of the node, mainly because node lacing can have a dramatic effect on the outcome of the whole graph.
  - Alternatively you could move the lacing switch to the title of the node. (or somewhere else?)

Right now the new toggle can get obstructed by other nodes. If the same is implemented for lacing, you should definitely make it so that the toggle is always visible and does not become obstructed by other nodes. Otherwise graph comprehension might suffer:

![revit_2016-01-24_11-43-33](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/12534353/3635231e-c290-11e5-871d-af7fc370da07.png)

Here's a quick sketch for the lacing suggestion:

![revit_2016-01-24_11-48-22](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7148394/12534371/b7823f6e-c291-11e5-962d-dabc767ec0b0.png)

@RodRecker  @Racel 
"

title: b'Unable to run'
body:
b"Dynamo 0.9.0
Windows 7
See attached for files

I'm working on a tutorial and I've created many connections (that could be part of the issue but it works until I change a connection). Either way, I create what I want to and then I get curious how other nodes would change the structure because the current connection looks complicated and I think I could simplify it to get the same result. I remove two nodes and two previous connections to insert one node and try to run it. Dynamo thinks for a few second and then acts as if it completed the run except it didn't. 

The run looks successful based on the button but nothing changes from then on. I can go into the geometry view and rotate and pan. I can go back into the node view and add nodes and alter connections. I can even save. However, nothing will change no matter what connections I alter. Trying to close the program does nothing and I eventually have to end task.

I understand I may not be able to do what I was trying to do but I thought it would give me an error box above the nodes like it normally does instead of freezing without really freezing.

[Dynamo Error.zip](https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/files/83298/Dynamo.Error.zip)
"

body:

When clicking the Browse button, **the Browse For Folder dialogue's start location should be set to the path currently stored in the node** (if that path exists, of course).

title: b'Small Wishes/Issues Collection'
body:
b"I apologize beforehand if some of these are already there. I checked as hard as I could.
I also want to let you know that I'm really not trying to be very demanding, simply reporting what I think would make Dynamo more amazing.

Wishes:
Split Surface for Topography
Ability to create multiple links instantly
Delete Input function (selected model gets replaced by the Dynamo output)
Select EdgeS(being able to select multiple edges from Revit)
Add to group/Remove from group function

Issues: Again, apologies if some of these are known, didn't find them in the list.
When I have some components selected, holding shift will add to the selection, but not when you drag and shift. Dragging deselects previous selections (even with Shift held).
Turning off the preview for multiple components can be a tedious task, once one has selected multiple components, turning off the preview will affect only one of them.

Thanks lots guys! Keep your head up with the outstanding work, and please let me know if my requests are valid. Best regards.
"

title: b'Text notes UI in Dynamo'
body:
b"I have noticed some weird Text Note UI behavior: 

It can be made really small: 

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/11569385/8e12ad6c-99bf-11e5-829e-fe6ca2554045.png)

Adding a Minimum Size property to that window might make sense. 

It can be collapsed so that controls/buttons disappear:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/11569423/c8c11034-99bf-11e5-92c8-d57acf711ca7.png)

Again, a min size constraint would fix that. 

It cannot be expanded however: 

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/11569436/e5cc38f2-99bf-11e5-8d87-b705d30b1a47.png)

There seems to be a Max Size applied to it. It only allows for 2 lines of text to be visible at a time making adding longer notes quite hard. 

It can be maximized to look like this: 

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/11569474/195e863e-99c0-11e5-9269-66c384802e27.png)

That's weird, maybe we disable the min and max boxes. 
Also, its visible in the task-bar as independent app: 

![untitled-6](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/11569508/48a64256-99c0-11e5-94f4-14411df53605.png)

That of course can be disabled as well. 

All in all, that text note editor might need some love. I bet others will have some comments about enabling font style, color, size etc. 

Thanks! 
"

https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/commit/1aa3d60b5985cdc40ee9f7999f223d1709cf1dd2

But the more worrying thing is that the update might have caused a regression.
I have no problem executing my code in Revit 2015 (or 2014 with 0.82), but in Revit 2016 the transaction manager seems to be unable to open multiple transactions:

Revit 2015:

title: b'Background preview not visible when preview is enabled AFTER graph execution'
body:
b"Dynamo 0.9 (can't test this on daily builds currently, so this may have been fixed already)

**Steps to reproduce:**
- Run a graph that contains geometry with background preview disabled
- Enable background preview
- No geometry is displayed

**Expected behaviour**:
After enabling background preview the geometry should be visible if the graph has already been executed. This is a regression BTW - it definitely used to work in 0.7 (don't have 0.8 installed right now, so I can't say anything about that version).

**Workaround:**
a) Set graph to automatic and connect a `Watch 3D` node to any geometry node
b) Change an input parameter of the graph and re-run
c) Re-wire sth. and re-run
"

title: b'Manage Packages.'
body:
b'Hi, this is an update to #4384. 
- Is it possible that the package search only shows packages available for the installed version of Dynamo? sometimes I want to install a package and it simply crashes when I try to use it (which I guess is most of the times a problem of the version the package is designed for and the one i have installed).

  Thanks

title: b'Read-Only server permissions and Node/Package Paths'
body:
b'I set up all the common packages and scripts in one location on our server thinking I could enable all users to use a common set of packages and custom nodes (using 0.8.2 - holding off on deploying 0.9 for a few weeks), tested it and it worked fine.....for me (I have full priviledges).  Then after pushing out to everyone, I start getting the calls that..."This doesn't work at all...Dynamo freezes up and won't run".  Lo and behold - it's the write permissions. 

Apparently, if the Custom Node and Package Path (and/or the location where pre-made scripts are saved) is Read-Only ....Dynamo-No-Go.  It literally freezes up as it starts to open.  Change the node paths to a location with full permission and open a script from your desktop - it works great.  Dynamo seemingly insists on having full write permission to ANY custom node/package path and to the location where a script is opened from.

Here's the rub - just because we want people using scripts we create doesn't mean we trust them enough to give them full permissions.  I think this needs to be addressed before 1.0 comes out for sure.....it's analogous to Revit Libraries - we have them set up as read-only to protect them from unwanted editors - once someone has loaded something, they can edit and use in their project, but the read-only permission on the server does not prevent them from opening Revit and loading files from the read-only library - it only prevents them from saving.  In Dynamo - the read-only permission literally prevents Dynamo from fully opening from the start.

Ideally, I would keep all of my scripts (intended for repeated re-use) and nodes/packages in a safe location on the server that can be accessed by all but not written to.  The user would then open a script from that location, run it on their project, and either throw away after it's run or save it to their project folder.  

Is there something in the way Dynamo is built that makes this impossible or is it just an oversight that can be easily fixed? I'm not good enough to work on the source code so all i can do is just post and hope someone can shed some light on this..
'

title: b'only one package can have icons (Package.customization.dll)'
body: b'@ikeough @mjkkirschner @pboyer It appears to me that currently only one package can have icons defined using Package.customization.dll Adding icons to ZeroTouch libraries works fine. That usually creates a customization file that has unique name based on namespace name ex: bbUI.customization.dll. Unless there are two packages with the same name, I don't think there will ever be a conflict with that method. However, the same name seems to throw off all of the customization files with the same name "Package". Only one of them will get loaded. For example my bumblebee package has both namespace and package customization files but since i already loaded icons via "package" customization file for Mantis shrimp, my bb icons don't get displayed. If I however, uninstall mantis shrimp, both icon sets get loaded nicely for bumblebee. Also, since my package name starts with "A" my icons load in, but @andydandy74 package doesn't load since his name starts with "C". All in all, it appears that only ONE (1) Package.customization.dll file can be loaded at the time. Can we make sure customization files work for more than one package? Thanks! '

title: b'attempt to modify the model outside of transaction'
body:
b'For some reason I can't post to Dynamobim forum. so I am posting here.

I wrote a python script that sets the parameter of some elements using the Set method of the parameter. It works for some elements but for most it doesn't with error message: "attempt to modify the model outside of transaction".

This is the whole code:

``` python
import System

import clr
clr.AddReference('RevitAPI')
clr.AddReference("RevitServices")

from Autodesk.Revit.DB import FilteredElementCollector
from RevitServices.Persistence import DocumentManager

doc = DocumentManager.Instance.CurrentDBDocument
cats = doc.Settings.Categories

# lookup tabe accepts csv format such as: foo,bar
lookupTable = {line.split(",")[0]:line.split(",")[1] for line in IN[0].splitlines()}
param = IN[1]
typeLimit = None
try:
    typeLimit = set(IN[2].splitlines())
except:
    pass

modifiedElements = []
for cat in cats:
    if cat.Name not in lookupTable:
        continue
    collector = FilteredElementCollector(doc)
    collector.OfCategoryId(cat.Id)
    for item in collector.ToElements():
        if typeLimit and str(item.GetType()).split(".")[-1] not in typeLimit:
            continue
        for p in item.Parameters:
            if p.Definition.Name == param:
                #try:
                    p.Set(lookupTable[cat.Name])
                    modifiedElements.append(item)
                #except:
                    #pass
OUT = modifiedElements
```
'

title: b'Need a node to set the active view in a Revit model'
body:
b'I thought I could do this by myself using a Python node, but no such luck.
Dynamo tells me that setting the active view is currently disabled.
Looks like this can only be done via a proper built-in Dynamo node.
FWIW, here's my Python code:

```
import clr
clr.AddReference('RevitAPI')
from Autodesk.Revit.DB import *
import Autodesk

clr.AddReference("RevitServices")
import RevitServices
from RevitServices.Persistence import DocumentManager
from RevitServices.Transactions import TransactionManager

doc = DocumentManager.Instance.CurrentDBDocument
uiapp = DocumentManager.Instance.CurrentUIApplication
uidoc = uiapp.ActiveUIDocument
view = UnwrapElement(IN[0])

TransactionManager.Instance.EnsureInTransaction(doc)
uidoc.ActiveView = view
TransactionManager.Instance.TransactionTaskDone()

OUT = view
```
'

title: b'Surface.Point.At.Parameter not aligning with XY object from Revit'
body:
b'When a Face, coming from an Floor object in Revit, which is not aligned with the main WCS X-axis, is connected to the Surface.PointAtParameter node, then the points are generated according to the global Dynamo X-axis and on the XY boundary box of the face. When the same script is done on a Face selection of a wall, which is also not aligned with the X-axis, then the points are nicely generated within the curves of the vertical face.

Read more and find datasets at Forum: http://dynamobim.com/forums/topic/surface-point-at-parameter-not-aligning-with-xy-object-from-revit/
'

title: b'Perimeter curves from surfaces'
body:
b'I have been trying to generate curves by intersecting a solid with a series of planes. This should in theory be a simple way to generate floors via curves, with the planes being floor levels. 

my approach is to create as solid from two poly curves, intersect with planes, and extract the perimeter curves from the resultant surfaces. Works fine on shapes with straight lines. However as soon as even a simple curve is added, the white screen of death comes up. I have tried many ways, poly surfaces, intersecting surfaces rather than solids to get the curves, but nothing seems to work. 

its odd, as the surface generates fine, you can get areas from it, and a linear perimeter length, all of which suggest that the perimeter is definable. 

any ideas? 
'

title: b'Fit Plane Issue'
body:
b"Hi, 
I tried this with version 0.8, Dynamo Studio, and v0.9.

The Plane.ByBestFitThroughPoints function seems to generate inconsistent results.

I pass a list of 4-point groups-- all made in the same order (ie: p0,p1,p2,p3). One should expect all planes' normals to be consistent since the points are constructed consistently. However, the generated plane come with different up/down normals.

to reproduce the issue:
-Make a surface, 
-Make two series for u and v, 
-feed the series to a PointAtParameter node with CrossProduct Lacing, 
-feed the points lists to a python script to organize them into groups of 4 points( script below), 
-pass the groups to a Plane.ByBestFitThroughPoints

here is the script:
pts =IN[0] # nested lists of points.
quads = []
for i in range(len(pts)-1):
    for j in range(len(pts[i])-1):
         p0 = pts[i][j]
         p1 = pts[i+1][j]
         p2 = pts[i+1][j+1]
         p3 = pts[i][j+1]
         quad = [p0, p1, p2, p3]
         quads.Add(quad)
OUT = quads

here is a screenshot of the graph
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5727365/10352512/5b3837aa-6d04-11e5-9de5-5d54fcc48316.png)

here is a screenshot of the issue
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5727365/10352361/77700d18-6d03-11e5-8a4f-5e81b8721e02.png)

Is this as expected?
"

title: b'Code Block - Internal Components -  Individual preview visibility control'
body:
b'Revit 2015, Dynamo 0.8.3.2632

When I convert a number of nodes to a code block (or simply author a code block from scratch that has many components within it (ie. Coordinate Systems, lines, points...), the code block shows ALL of its internal components in the geometry preview.  I know a workaround is to turn preview off for the code block entirely, and then attach "preview" code blocks to the outputs for which a preview is desired.  But for lengthy codeblocks, especially those where a majority of the components wish to remain visible but some do not, it would be nice to override the visibility of the components individually, possibly by right clicking (or simply single-left-clicking) the output arrow, or through some internal syntax to flag the item as "not visible".

If you'd like to see a longer description with images, forum discussion is here:
http://dynamobim.com/forums/topic/design-script-selective-onoff-visibility-for-internal-components/

Cheerio!

NC
'

title: b'Python Script node not working in Dynamo 0.8.3.2256'
body:
b"Hello, 
Please find below my issue.
Thank you for your time. (I also posted something on the forum just in case someone already had this issue)

1.Which version of Dynamo are you using (check the About box)?
0.8.3.2256 (revit 2016)
2.Which operating system are you using?
Windows 10
3.What did you do?
Tried to run a script that was working 10 days ago (Dynamo script containing python script nodes). It crashed directly but after having disabled part of my script I was able to see that the problem comes from the Python script node
4.What did you expect to see?
My python scripts that were working before are not working anymore. I am not able to edit them anymore (even on a new project). Dynamo crashes directly.

title: b'Iterating Dynamo Definition with Revit Objects'
body:
b'I am trying to drive a small test building geometry parametrically through Dynamo. This geometry will then be converted to Revit elements either in Dynamo or through the Revit interface. I am running into the following issues:
- If I create the geometry entirely in Dynamo, and use import instance into a mass family, I can create elements in the project \xe2\x80\x9cby face.\xe2\x80\x9d However when I update the geometry at a later date, all the \xe2\x80\x9cby face\xe2\x80\x9d elements are deleted because they can\xe2\x80\x99t find their original hosts. I thought Dynamo updated the geometry? It looks like its recreating it instead.
- Next I tried to create reference lines form Dynamo and either create forms form these \xe2\x80\x9cbones\xe2\x80\x9d or snap points / lines to create forms from, and the same issue presents itself. The forms get deleted if created directly from the Dynamo reference lines, or the points get left behind if a parameter is changed in Dynamo.

Has anything broken with regards to the Revit / Dynamo interoperability? I have tested this with the latest stable release 0.8.2. Which the latest dailies (0.8.3.20150921T0452) the Revit geometry is not even instantiated.

I tried this first with an adaptive Revit family, but the constraints brake easily and its not robust. The constraints work wonderfully in Dynamo, but then you can\xe2\x80\x99t update the Revit elements after design iterations

title: b'CSV.WriteToFile should not add whitespace in front of strings'
body:
b'I have a workflow that will read and write the same CSV file multiple times. What I have observed is that the CSV.WriteToFile node seems to add a whitespace in front of every string. The effect is that Dynamo adds another whitespace each time the CSV file is written again, like so (whitespace replaced by underscores for readability):
Original: `item1,item2,item3`
Iteration 1: `item1,_item2,_item3`
Iteration 2: `item1,__item2,__item3`
Iteration 3: `item1,___item2,___item3`
and so on.
Expected behaviour: Do not add whitespace between delimiter and string
Workaround: Use `String.TrimWhitespace` to get rid of the whitespace before writing the CSV file. Unfortunately this does not work as soon as the CSV file also contains numeric data.
0.8.3.2580
'

title: b'Placing the same node multiple times from in-canvas search'
body:
b'When searching for a node in the browser we can hit the Return key multiple times to place the same node over and over again (I tend do this a lot e.g. with Watch nodes). When using the in-canvas search this, unfortunately, is not possible. Instead when hitting Return for the second time (and each subsequent time), the last search result from the _browser_ (if any) gets placed. 

It would be great if Dynamo could remember which search field (browser / context menu) was last used and place the respective node on each subsequent use of the Return key. An alternative would be for Dynamo to remember the search term used in the in-canvas search so we can achieve the desired result with a combination of right-click and Return (deleting the search term from the in-canvas search field could be done with Esc key - just like in the browser).

Dynamo 0.8.2
'

title: b'Flatten is ignored in custom nodes with specified input data types'

title: b'Element Binding/Dynamo not properly deleting elements after closing and Re-Opening Revit "Project File" and Re-running DYN File'
body:
b'I have been trying to troubleshoot this issue, and have narrowed it down to one specific situation. Any help/insight into this would be greatly appreciated.

Let's say I have, for example, opened a new Revit Project File and I have a DYN file that is reading point data from excel and breaking this data up to apply to an AdaptivePoints Component. If I:

1) Run the Script
          -Element ID's are generated
2) Save the Excel File (this will make Dynamo re-compute the script when I hit Run) and run the                                        script
          -Element ID's remain the same
3) "Save As" Excel file with a new name and run the script
          -Element ID's remain the same
4)Use different excel file with point data (just a previous design version, so the point data is different) and run the script
          -Element ID's remain the same
5)Save the Revit Project File and Dyn File, close and re-open the files, and run the script
          -Element ID's have changed
          -New Adaptive Components have been generated on top of the old ones and the old ones are
           remain          

The problem occurs when this Revit Project File, a model containing only the facade of a building, is linked back into the central model. Now that these facade elements have new element ID's, all annotation (DIMS, keynotes, etc.,) are blown away. As you can imagine this becomes a problem during the documentation process. Is this a unique issue or something that is currently being worked? I found this conversation that discusses a similar issue, (https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/pull/301) but sounds as the issue has been fixed. Running Revit 2015 and Dynamo 0.8.2.2392.
'

title: b'Displaying Custom Zero-Touch Node Data in a Watch Window'
body:
b'Is there an attribute that can be added to a zero touch node to make it's data display in a Dynamo watch node?

That is, assume I have a zero-touch node written in C# called "MyDynamoNode", which has a method "ByNumber" that takes a number and returns a MyDynamoNode that has the number stored internally. If I look at the return value of MyDynamoNode.ByNumber in a watch window it says "MyDynamoNode". I would like the watch window to display the number that is stored in my node instead of the node type. I am assuming this is possible, as it is done for Dynamo native items such as Point.

Also, if there are any other attributes that are generally useful for zero-touch node programming can you please say what they are? I have seen one that says "don't expose in Dynamo", and I assume that there are other attributes but I have not been able to find any documentation about this. Any helpful tips would be greatly appreciated.

Thanks much.
'

title: b'Nurbs Surfaces - weight property returns null '
body:
b'This is related to work that I am doing with Mantis Shrimp hence geometry that I am dealing with is coming from Grasshopper originally. 

I have a RevSurface that I am exporting to Dynamo. I conveniently convert it to NurbsSurface (since at the moment RhinoCommon has not exposed any ON_RevSurface properties) and export to Dynamo. It all works great. I get exactly the same Nurbs Surface in Dynamo. Awesome! 

Here is the trick:

When I try to take this - now DS - surface and export it back to Grasshopper a little funny thing occurs to me. Somehow, somewhere Dynamo figured that this Nurbs Surface was rational (IsRational property returns True) and it now refuses to return Weights(). This is a major letdown here since I quite need those Weights to be able to re-create this exact same Nurbs Surface again in Rhino/Grasshopper. 
Since Dynamo refuses to return Weights of rational Nurbs Surfaces, does it mean that it assumes that they are all equal to 1? This is most definitely not the case here. 

Thank you,

@pboyer @ptierney @kronz @ikeough 
'

Tom

body: b'Isn\'t this node supposed to report the level elevation based on the Project Basepoint, or am I misinterpreting its function? title: b'background preview'
body:
b'When navigating a background preview in Dynamo:

Zoom To Fit  - zooms to objects but also zooms to origin so if objects generated in canvas are far from the origin then zoom to fit is useless since it really zooms to extents (origin included).
If objects are far from origin then its impossible to zoom in on them or even rotate them. It would be nice to be able to center our origin on geometry by selecting a node on canvas so when we rotate the center of rotation is our selected geometry. Also it would be nice to zoom into the selected geometry. 
'

title: b'Migration issue: Custom nodes get migrated by name not by unique ID'
body: b"I just ran into this by accident. There are custom nodes called List.ChopByLengths in both the Ampersand and the Clockwork package. When migrating a graph that contains both nodes from 0.7 to 0.8 all instances of those nodes will be set to the node from the Ampersand package. Why do custom nodes have unique IDs when they aren't used in a process as crucial as migrating a workflow to the next Dynamo version?\n0.8.1 RC 2\n"

title: b'Bug in 0.8.0'
body:
b"See also this thread: http://dynamobim.com/forums/topic/find-mass-floors-mass-id/

I am comparing geometry extacted from Mass Floors (Element.Faces) to geometry extracted from the intersection of horizontal planes at created at the elevation of the project Levels and solid geometry obtained from Masses. (Geometry.IntersectAll).

Unexpected result is that at a certain distance from origin, the geometry from the intersection of the panes and solid geometry gets cropped to a cylindrical volume that is centered around the origin, see image.

![capture1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/12673938/8455524/999015dc-2005-11e5-8a77-bc949626c2f0.png)

That in turn causes a mismatch when I try to compare the geometry at the edge of this 'ghost' cylinder to the geometry from the Mass Floor faces, not to mention missing stuff outside the cylindrical \xe2\x80\x98range\xe2\x80\x99.

Anyone recognize this behaviour? Perhaps fixed in daily build? Solutions to circumvent?
"

title: b'\xe2\x80\x98Polysurface.ByLoftGuides\xe2\x80\x99 bug'
body:
b'Hi,

There seems to be an issue with the way \xe2\x80\x98Polysurface.ByLoftGuides\xe2\x80\x99 handles NURBS profiles.

I constructed a simple file to explain the bug. It contains 4 guide curves (also NURBScurves) and 2 sets of 2 profile curves (NURBScurves).

Profile set 1 was created by the \xe2\x80\x98NurbsCurve.ByPoints\xe2\x80\x99 node. When I loft these profiles along the 4 NURBSguides everything is fine and works as expected. See image 1.

Profile set 2 was created by the \xe2\x80\x98NurbsCurve.ByControlPoints\xe2\x80\x99 node. When I loft these profiles the 4 NURBSguides get ignored and the result is a straight loft. No yellow warning is presented. See image 2.

In my opinion this is a bug. Is this the right place to report this issue? Can something be done about this or is this normal behavior?

title: b'Surface.ByPatch Fails on Complex Imported NURBS Curves'

b'I am trying to recreate some surfaces that were created in CATIA in Revit. I can import the CATIA file into AutoCAD and get it into Revit, but the number of control points wreaks havoc on the wall by face operations and causes them to fail.

So, instead of working with the original surfaces, I am trying to recreate them in a more simplified way. The loss of fidelity is acceptable in this case because its purpose is to make drawings in Revit.

Out of 65 surfaces I have 5 that refuse to work with Surface.ByPatch. All of the curves are closed polycurves. It gives me the following error:

title: b'Some suggested improvements for German localization'
body:
b'@monikaprabhu - as per #4564 I am submitting some suggestions on how to improve German localization:

`File` menu:
- `Export Model to STL`: **"Modell als STL exportieren..."** (This would be more consistent with the translation used for `Export Workspace as Image`: `Arbeitsbereich als Bild exportieren`
- `Recent Files`: **"Zuletzt benutzte Dateien"** or (better yet) **"Zuletzt verwendete Dateien**" (This is the wording that is commonly used across a wide array of applications. The current wording's literal translation is "last", not "recent".)

`View` menu:
- `Connectors`: There is a German word for this that does _not_ have latin roots: **"Verbinder"**

`Console` :
- `00:00:01.4474435 elapsed for loading Dynamo main window.`: **"00:00:01.4474435 verstrichen zum Laden des Dynamo Hauptfensters"** (a bit of grammar)

title: b'Dynamo solids converted to meshes instead of solids '
body:
b'When using python scripts, Dynamo curves are transformed smoothly to Revit curve geometry objects by using ToRevitType(). So using the Revit API it is quite straightforward to create some Revit elements not supported yet by the current Revit Dynamo nodes. Like for example making detail lines in the active view.

Sadly Dynamo solids are not converted to Revit solid geometry objects by using ToRevitType(). The result is mesh geometry objects instead. Maybe there is here a limitation of the Revit API.

I know that the integration in Revit of "external" solid geometry is an important area of development. Hopefully future versions of Revit will improve this 
'

title: b'Wish: Package Manager functionalities'
body:
b'I like to add some additional suggestions to issue #3920 which may be closed since most things seem to work in the current builds?!
- Update packages: The context menu in package manager should have an update functionality. This would be much easier then uninstalling the package and search for them to install them again.
- the search should have an option to show/hide deprecated packages (this is sometimes confusing. e.g. when you are searching for "Clockwork")
- if a depending package is already installed, do not reinstall it (eg when installing dynanimator with clockwork already installed).
- below the library in the "Add" dropdown there should also be the possibility to add local packages/costum nodes. This should allow users to browse a local path or dyf file and add a copy to either C:\Users<USER>\AppData\Roaming\Dynamo\0.8\definitions or \packages and add them to the library. Best would be to also have a checkbox "remove/keep original file".

Thanks, Fabian
'

title: b'UI/UX Wish / Feedback:  More Straightforward Tree View of Nodes (0.8+)'
body:
b'Hello all,
Here is some feedback from recent workshops and my own personal exploration of Dynamo 0.8...  the introduction of icons is pretty cool, but the UI for navigating the library has become much more complex and confusing.  The user must now use three 'styles' of navigation to reach their nodes.  I found the previous (0.7 and earlier) tree view is far more navigation friendly.  Why not just introduce icons to the old navigation?

The following is an attempt to explain why this new UI is confusing to both myself and, especially, new users.

Starting out:  When starting Dynamo, the library gives the expectation of a "tree"-style UI like the previous versions and most other programs.
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1890663/7106251/6468e986-e100-11e4-9a3c-9881e237df87.png)

Expanding the Tree:  Expanding the "Core" library, I am now presented with a grid of icons.  My first reaction is "ah, cool! node icons!"   At this point I am expecting that Tree = categories, Icons = nodes.
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1890663/7106328/02a7c36e-e102-11e4-9445-82ff39748f35.png)

Confused Navigation:  This is where things get muddy.  Upon clicking on any these icons, it is revealed that icons are actually categories, too.  Clicking on any of these icons, the interface now introduces a "tab"-style navigation with nodes represented as a "list".  At this stage, the user has gone through 3 styles of navigation to get to a node...
1.  Tree Names
2.  Icon Grid
3.  List of Icons
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1890663/7106339/90ef66cc-e102-11e4-865d-ff23408c6a96.png)

As we continue to expand icons and look around, the navigation becomes nearly incoherent... I see category icons, node icon lists, and trees all at once.  Where should I click?
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1890663/7106386/6a7044f6-e104-11e4-82ea-c2720164a45b.png)

Tree View is Much Easier:  Now let's contrast this with the basic 0.7 tree view.  It is very straight forward.  It isn't as "pretty", but Icons could easily be added to this without the need for additional navigation UI.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1890663/7106434/5233a70a-e106-11e4-8566-ecd795f36e79.png)
'

title: b'Switching between Dynamo versions'
body:
b"I really like the fact that there's a version switcher for Dynamo 0.7 and 0.8 - but it shows some - in my opinion - erratic behaviour:
After having switched the version the version switcher is greyed out:
![nomoreswitchingversions](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3014437/6893002/80b80518-d6c9-11e4-8cbf-82e52691e537.PNG)
Only after restrating Revit is it possible to use the version switcher again:
![versionswitcherafterrestart](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3014437/6893012/970800de-d6c9-11e4-82ea-03f05f690b88.PNG)
The previous version switcher (0.63 vs. 0.7) worked differently: after switching to a different version we had to restart Revit (and were notified of that necessity) which I found a lot more logical in terms of UX.
"

title: b'Autorun enabled by default'
body:
b"It's a bad idea to by default have Auto-run on in Dynamo. It's not Grasshopper and its performing a lot heavier operations than Grasshopper. I think it was good as it was before when it was on Manual to begin with and user could switch to Auto-run. Why? 
Well, for starters Dynamo doesn't Auto-save so any screw-up is a fatal one. There is no getting your work back. 
Second, it ports into Revit and does some heavy lifting. Any screw-up and you are going to crash faster than you can count to two. 
Please roll that change back to what it was. There is no benefit in Auto-running Dynamo. 
"

title: b'Wishlist: Dynamo solids to Revit voids'
body:
b'Probably the way that the solid geometry created in Dynamo is \xe2\x80\x9cimported\xe2\x80\x9d in Revit will be greatly enhanced soon. Anyway this can be an easy but practical possibility.

Recently I have been working many times creating solid geometry in Dynamo that will subtract other elements. But this operation is doing in Revit via \xe2\x80\x9cCut\xe2\x80\x9d. This way of working is rather  convenient and flexible for many reasons.

Right now, every time that I create the solid geometry in Dynamo I have to:
1.Move the elements to Revit via ImportInstance.ByGeometry 
2.Explode the imported instance in Revit
3.Change the type of solid to \xe2\x80\x9cvoid\xe2\x80\x9d

A method that put the solid geometry in Revit directly as Revit solid would avoid having to explode the element every time. And ideally you will have the option that the element will be a \xe2\x80\x9cvoid\xe2\x80\x9d, so you don\xe2\x80\x99t have to change the type manually .
'

import sys

axis = Autodesk.Revit.DB.Line.CreateBound(center,center + XYZ.BasisZ)

# Assign your output to the OUT variable

OUT = debug

title: b'WISH - flat list to list of lists mapping per index'
body:
b'Not sure I'm describing this well in the title, however here's what I'm after.

Let's say I have List "A" and List "B". I make List "B" as part of a function and wire it to the f(x) port. I then wire List "A" to the list port. All members of List "B" are mapped to every member of List "A". This produces a new, larger list with multiple nested sublists, depending on the amount of nesting in each list. However what I'm after is as follows:

a) Let's say List "A" is a flat list whose count is "n". List "B" is a list containing "n" nested lists (list of lists). Each sublist can vary in size.
b) I want to create a similar map as described above, however I want to map the first member of List "A" with all the members of the first sublist in List "B", then the second member of List "A" with all the members of the second sublist in List "B", etc.
c) In summary, map f(List "B" Sublist index [n] - all members) to List "A" index [n].

For the life of me (and with no Python knowledge whatsoever), I cannot find a way to do this except through recursion. I could build a custom node that extracts the first index of each list and maps them, then moves on to the next, [n] times. However recursion is too slow and will not be scalable. Thanks.
'

title: b'Package Manager UI'
body:
b'I'm noticing a few things in the Manage Package dialog, some of which might be considered "wishes for improvements" and some might be bugs. I'm running 0.7.5.3566.

a) When in the Package Manager, I see the packages installed but I have no way of telling who the author is. If we're required to go to the website to find out, it would be nice to have a direct link to that package (ex: right-click context menu?).

b) When selecting "Show Contents", the mouse scroll does not work. You have to pick on the tiny scroll bar and move it, which can be a bit of a painful experience.

c) Shouldn't "Show Contents" receive a check mark or change name to "Hide Contents" when this is invoked? It is unintuitive to click on "Show Contents" again to hide the contents.

d) When I opened a .dyn workspace that depended on a few custom .dyf nodes on a machine that did not have them installed, I received no warning. The workspace just seemed to stop working around the custom nodes, at which point then I realized what was happening. After installing the packages and closing and re-opening Dynamo, then things started working again. There needs to be better support for this, such as perhaps automatically prompting the user to download and install the relevant packages. This is even more important when custom nodes are wrapped within other custom nodes and the problem why a custom node isn't working will not be as easily identified by the average user.

My apologies if the above have already been logged! Thanks.
'

title: b'Possible bug when writing parameters of length'
body:
b'Probably you know about this and the solution is on the way, but in any case\xe2\x80\xa6.

Typical scenario: I have a project in revit in mm. I extract some geometry with Dynamo and because Dynamo internal units are in meter  the results are in meter. Imagine a Point with X=100000mm in Revit. When I extract the X coordinate in Dynamo the value is 100, as expected. Everything is fine until now.

But now I want to write that value to a parameter of an entity of Revit, so I can extract that information in Revit without having to run the dynamo file. I use SetParameterByName. The type of parameter is Length.

When later I check the parameter in Revit I will see that the value is \xe2\x80\xa6.30 480, which is exactly 100 feet in mm. So when dynamo is writing the value is \xe2\x80\x9cforgetting\xe2\x80\x9d that its own internal units are meter.

Adding just  *3.2808399 before writing the parameter will take care of this. But can be extremely confusing at the beginning if you don\xe2\x80\x99t know what is going on.
'

title: b'G1 Discontinuity and Nurbs Curves handling while creating floors'
body:
b"A Dynamo user has asked me for help the other day, and here are some of the issues that I was able to pinpoint for him:

Hi Paul,

I had a quick look at your definition. Here's what the problem was. Your curves were joined into a single polycurve which normally is OK. However, for some reason in this instance it caused Dynamo to freak out and report this error:
https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/issues/2643
Same error reported here by Rhynamo package creator Nate.
https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/issues/3620

It's clearly a Dynamo issue and has been bugging both of us. My workaround for this type of situation is to explode the polycurves. 

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054160/e6e08d92-acb7-11e4-9193-8da5b5f2a019.png)

That's exactly what I am doing in this very simple Grasshopper definition. I first explode them in Rhino. Reference them in, join them, explode them again and make sure they are on 4 separate branches. I probably could have just referenced them in joined and explode in GH avoiding the extra join step but anyways i digress. 

The idea here is to pass four (4) lists of curves where if all curves from each list were to be joined again you will get that one single floor outline.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054165/f5019236-acb7-11e4-9d39-82024fc33966.png)

This works quite well! I am sorry this is such a hassle, but Dynamo is a little behind on handling polycurves. There are a lot of issues with them at the moment, and I am still waiting on some solutions from the Dynamo team. 

Just to make sure that you are good to go I went ahead and tried to create the floors....well no luck! Here's my error message:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054171/02c181b0-acb8-11e4-9dd6-69de7a6f1e91.png)

This is simply a Dynamo being horrible at understanding what Revit wants. This error as much as its not very common it will get thrown when you try to generate a Nurbs Curve in Revit with degree less than 3. 

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054175/0bddd6c2-acb8-11e4-9464-ad07f65c2acf.png)

Since one of the curves in your floor outline is a NurbsCurve of second (2) degree it will not be very welcome by Revit. Here's a screen capture of Revit API exceptions for the NurbsCurves:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054177/15061c82-acb8-11e4-8fd1-603c70a5bf2a.png)

So, here's a few options for you. Either go back to Rhino, and remodel those curves to up their degree to 3 or more. It's very simple, just rebuild that curve. Second option is to complain to Dynamo team about this. Third option is to handle the floor creation yourself via a custom node, and build in a check for Nurbs Curves that have degree less than 3 and up their degree then or convert them to Revit's closest approximation which is a Hermite Spline. 

It's not a perfect world we live in so I recommend rebuilding the curves in Rhino. Like so:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054180/1efb4b5e-acb8-11e4-8fc1-cb669aa894c6.png)

And it still fails:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054183/27e4a760-acb8-11e4-97d1-2909de33a91c.png)

Clearly the Nurbs Curves are not very welcome in Revit. What we can do with that i guess is convert them all to lines and arcs. 

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054187/31932674-acb8-11e4-9f48-1e0369939bba.png)

You can use Rhino command called Convert. 

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054189/3af5ef76-acb8-11e4-99bf-47a31291d9de.png)
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/529781/6054191/3ef42250-acb8-11e4-943c-2c2559d5d473.png)

Success! 

All in all this was an exercise in how not compatible Dynamo geometry is with Revit geometry. 
"

title: b'Surface error:  IG_SURFACE_NON_G1:  Surface is G1 Discontinous'
body:
b'Every now and then, I get this error when constructing a NURBS surface with NurbsSurface.ByControlPointsWeightsKnots():  "IG_SURFACE_NON_G1:  Surface is G1 Discontinous"

For example, here is a NURBS surface I would like to describe inside of Dynamo...
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1890663/5893383/160feab8-a4a7-11e4-92f8-68806b57eb86.png)

The NURBS geometry is originally defined in Rhino.  The surface is DegreeU = 1, DegreeV = 2, NumberOfPointsU = 2, NumberOfPointsV = 5.  

In most cases, NurbsSurface.ByControlPointsWeightsKnots works like a charm.  But there are still surfaces that are give this problem... even basic ones like the example above.

I found others that have had similar problems in Fusion.... http://forums.autodesk.com/t5/sketching-sculpting-modeling-and/quot-surface-g1-is-discontinuous-quot-preventing-ts-to-brep/td-p/5028854

There is also a report of this in AutoCAD:  http://forums.autodesk.com/t5/autocad-2010-2011-2012/how-to-create-a-complex-3d-solid-for-buildings-ceiling/td-p/3946807
'

body:
b'The overall problem is to take in all the door elements in the project, sort them by level and then re-number the doors sequentially.  I have managed to grab the elements, extract the parameters I need (Unique Revit ID, Level, Mark) and lace them into a list of lists so that each door is its own list.

The problem I'm having is that it will not sort by level.  When I get the parameter level Dynamo spits out the unique Revit ID of the level so in my list of 300-ish doors there are 8 unique levels.  I think maybe I don't understand the "keyList" or "keyProjector" parameter.  I am trying to feed it the function GetItematIndex that points to the index of the level.  

What is a keyProjector?
How do I sort a list of lists based on a particular index of the sublists?
Is this the right method to renumber doors sequentially?

Help would be appreciated.

title: b'Please Read: Repo Restructuring'
body:
b"Hi All - I would like to make you aware of some important restructuring that we're doing to the code over the next week. This work may require some changes in how you develop for Dynamo.

Today, we have activated work that provides a clean separation between the Dynamo core code and the Revit-specific integration code. This will streamline our efforts by reducing the need to merge between master branch and the Revit 2015 branch. It provides a clear path for adding future versions of Revit integration and forms a template for how other applications may be integrated with Dynamo.

For more details, please see these wiki pages:
\xe2\x80\xa2 [How to: Build DynamoRevit](https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/wiki/How-to:-Build-DynamoRevit%3F)

\xe2\x80\xa2 [Project structure in DynamoRevit as compared to Dynamo](https://github.com/DynamoDS/DynamoRevit/wiki/Project-structure-in-DynamoRevit-as-compared-to-Dynamo)

There are additional efforts underway to Dynamo core that will more carefully modularize DynamoCore.  This will ease multi-platform development, testing, and ensure Dynamo is stable and maintainable into the foreseeable future. In short, good things to do that will help everyone using and developing for Dynamo.

For developers who\xe2\x80\x99ve implemented \xe2\x80\x9czero-touch\xe2\x80\x9d libraries, this won\xe2\x80\x99t affect them at all.  

For developers who reference DynamoCore.dll in their node libraries, expect significant changes:

\xe2\x80\xa2 DynamoCore will be separated into DynamoCore and DynamoCoreWpf.  This separates DynamoCore into a WPF specific component.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Developers with NodeModel classes with custom user interfaces will need to also reference DynamoCoreWpf.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Developers with NodeModel classes with custom user interfaces will now need to implement a special INodeViewCustomization interface.  For most developers, this will be a simple copy-paste operation.

\xe2\x80\xa2 NodeModel will no longer receive a WorkspaceModel in the constructor.  Developers will need to access workspace level services through new, more secure API\xe2\x80\x99s.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Developers with NodeModel classes that have custom re-evaluation logic will need to replace all usages of RequiresRecalc with the new NodeModel.OnModified() method.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Developers with NodeModel classes that have custom Save and Load logic will need to use the new SerializeCore/DeserializeCore methods, as the old SaveNode/LoadNode methods have been deprecated.

Watch for these changes over the course of the next week.

As always, please let us know if you have questions or comments and thank you for your continued support of Dynamo.

Rod Recker
"

title: b'Feedback on Workflow for Updating Library-based Package'
body:
b'I recently updated a library-based package for Dynamo (Rhynamo).  I found the following which made the process quite tedious for both a developer and a user

From the Developer's side....
- When I update my library with a new version number, the library will no longer load in Dynamo through the package.  I thought I was going crazy because it didn't occur to me that changing the version number on the library would affect if it got loaded
- Following this, in order to get the library to load, I discovered that I also needed to update the pkg.json file by finding the line where it lists the library version and change it to the new version.
  ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1890663/5195727/62353b56-74ef-11e4-8e3f-58dce03cc845.png)

From the Users Side...
This appears to the be the workflow for a user who needs to update a library-based package like Rhynamo...
-  User goes to package manager.
-  User selects the package to update
-  Dynamo downloads package
-  Dynamo says something like "cannot uninstall old package, the old package will be removed but you need to restart Dynamo" (if you are in Revit, you have to restart Revit)
-  After restart, the package is removed... but the new version isn't there
-  User goes to the package manager
-  User selects the package to install
-  Dynamo downloads / installs the package.

A preferred workflow...
-  User goes to package manager
-  User selects package to update
-  Dynamo downloads package. 
-  User is alerted:  "The new version will be available after you restart Dynamo"
-  New package is available after restart.

Or better yet...
-  User goes to package manager
-  User selects package to update
-  Dynamo unloads old libraries and loads new libraries  (no restart needed)
'

title: b'Uninstalling Library-based Pacakge Requires Restart of Revit (not just Dynamo)'

If you do this within Revit, I have also found that you also need to restart Revit for this process to be successful which is rather inconvenient.

Suggestions...
-- Make it possible to uninstall library-based packages from within Revit (preferred)
-- Make it clear to the user that a restart of Revit is required (will at least clarify the workflow)
'

title: b'Library dependencies trying to load into Dynamo from Package'
body:
b'Hello all,
I am trying to prepare a package which depends on providing several libraries (dlls) in addition to a Dynamo zero touch library.  I am noticing that Dynamo attempts to load any library that is included in the package.  In my case, things seem to load correctly... but it seems this could have unintended consequences in other circumstances.

Here is a screenshot of dependencies attempting to load into Dynamo... these should not be loaded into Dynamo at all and are referenced by another library.
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1890663/5051279/199d4cba-6c04-11e4-8fa0-aaa38c4d68c3.png)

In my case, my "Rhynamo" tool ships with the following...  only "CASE_Rhynamo.dll" should get loaded by Dynamo.  The others are reference.
- "CASE_Rhynamo.dll" (this is the zero touch library that exposes new nodes... this is the only library that should be loaded)
- "CASE_RhinoConnection.dll" (a custom library referenced by Rhynamo)
- "Rhino3dmIO.dll" (the OpenNURBS library referenced by Rhynamo)
- "rhino3dmio_native.dll" (the C++ library referenced by OpenNURBS)

I should note that Grasshopper defines a special extension for dll libraries that get loaded as plug-ins.  For example, a dll with a "gha" extension would get loaded into Grasshopper, whereas other dlls provided as dependencies are not loaded.
'

title: b'About the geometry preview in Revit 2015 R2'
body:
b'Some comments to add to https://github.com/DynamoDS/Dynamo/issues/2542
-The current background geometry preview in Dynamo have a few issues. I know that there is a totally new one in the works. But until then, using the Revit environment seems quite convenient. I like a lot to have a screen only for the nodes and another one for the preview of the geometry. 
-If you are playing with geometry taken from Revit is really nice to leave \xe2\x80\x9con\xe2\x80\x9d run automatically, modify the base Revit geometry and see almost in real time how the dynamo geometry update in the same window.  
-The visualization seems to be a lot faster and more fluid. With many elements in screen and a close view the difference is huge.
-Some important current issues:
1.Not all the elements are previewed, like for example planes and coordinate systems.
2.When clicking a node the related elements are not highlighted.
3.The graphical appearance seems to be shadowed with transparency, with edges only in the silhouette. This can be \xe2\x80\x9ccool\xe2\x80\x9d, but is really not very practical. Having the transparency and not drawing all the edges is really confusing. I rather prefer having something like shadowed with edges. 
-One small issue:
After activating the preview and running again the graphic you are not going to see it, until you change some part of the graphic (or modify a Revit element that it is imported)
'

title: b'Selected category / element type is not always remembered across Revit versions'
body:
b'Nodes that include a dropdown in their UI seem to store their selected value based on the indices of the available options in the dropdown, e.g. in the Categories dropdown it might look like `index="894:Walls"`. Since different Revit versions have different numbers of categories or perhaps even element types one may currently _lose_ the originally selected category when opening a graph on top of a different Revit version. It would be very helpful if both Categories and Element Types were identified by their respective names instead of their order in the stack as the name property is actually less likely to change from one Revit version to the next.
Some use cases that are affected by this issue:
- Using the same graph on Revit projects of varying versions 
- Sharing work with people that work on a different Revit version than oneself
- Including a Categories or Element Types node in a custom node
'

Quite a few people were musing about different ways of accessing graphs. Here are the topics/suggestions that came up:
- Accessing finished graphs directly from the ribbon (similar to how one could add Python scripts to the ribbon with the RevitPythonShell)
- Collapsing a graph into a single UI that only shows all input elements (sliders etc.) and possibly outputs but none of the logic
- Running graphs in hidden mode (not seeing Dynamo at all)
- Have Dynamo graphs triggered by events in Revit (similar to a macro?)
- Combinations of all of the above
'

title: b'Best practice to visualize analysis results with Dynamo'
body:
b"@ksobon and I are trying to bring the results of the analysis from a 3rd party application into Revit using Dynamo.

The input is a colored mesh. There is a value assigned to each mesh vertices/mesh Face, so we can extract the values in different ways. Having the values and the points what is the best practice to visualize the results using Dynamo?

title: b'Units awareness when importing and exporting SAT files?'
body:
b"It seems that recently have been changed the behavior when importing and exporting SAT files. Before Dynamo didn't take into account the units information of the sat file and everything were imported 1 to 1.

In my case that I import from (and export to) a mm working environment, that means that until now I had a Scale(0.001) after every import and a Scale(1000) before every export. Not a big deal in Dynamo to do this.

Anyway it seems that this is not going to be needed anymore, even for exporting (the sat files from dynamo now they are starting with 1000 in the third line) . Just a little bit of a pity that this wasn't done before, because now I will have to delete all these scale everywhere if I open any previous definition with the last daily builds ups.

May I ask if someone can clearly confirm my assumptions about this? I have seen any pull request mentioning or explaining this.

Thanks.
"

title: b"What's the assumed workflow regarding units?"
body:
b"This issue contains a few wishes / feature requests - but mainly I'd just like to understand the reasoning behind some things regarding units in Dynamo that strike me as odd.
1. All the nodes that measure lengths, areas or volumes in Dynamo return doubles. If they have to return doubles, shouldn't they at least also return the respective units (*second output+)?
   ![getunits](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3014437/4283943/fcc5d470-3d75-11e4-8cd5-1522535d7da6.PNG)
2. Mathematical operations with units seem to be a very delicate matter:
   ![operators](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3014437/4284015/1c03ef7e-3d77-11e4-95e4-786a7ffd7500.PNG)
   In particular, I'd be interested in whether there is a _syntax for performing mathematical operations on mixed sets of data (e.g. doubles and lengths) in a CBN_. I, for one, couldn't figure it out. Creating complex formulas in a purely node-based workflow is clunky at best and seems to me a rather big step backward.
3. There do not seem to be any methods for verifying whether a number (e.g. an input value of a custom node) is, for example, a double or a length. As long as mathematical operations with units are so unforgiving, this poses a problem when designing custom node. i think we might need _IsLength, IsArea & IsVolume_.
4. My feeling is that due to the issues described above the use of units in Dynamo currently does not really make much sense. The only benefit I see at present is the use of conversion methods when interacting with the Revit API via Python. When pulling data out of the model these methods (FromFeet, FromSquareFeet, FromCubicFeet) work fine. ~~However, when feeding data to the Revit API we would need similar methods that work the other way (_ToFeet, ToSquareFeet, ToCubicFeet_).~~ 

Final question: What is the actual intended use for units in Dynamo? Is there any practical use case besides Revit API interaction that I am missing?
"

The package manager always returns the "Cannot Download Package" warning ("Dynamo needs to uninstall XXX to continue, but cannot as one of its types appears to be in use. Try restarting Dynamo.").\nWorkaround: Uninstall package manually and subsequently re-install.\n'

title: b'Solid.UnionAll changed?'
body:
b'The working of Solid.UnionAll seems to have changed to be similar to Solid.Union

We now seem to have to specify one solid and then a list of solids to combine with that solid. 
Earlier, it just combined a list of solids.

It was better in the earlier form.

Regards,
Vikram Subbaiah
'

title: b'wall tool problem'
body:
b'When I feed an arc into the wall tool it creates a longer arc. There is a wall connecting at either end at the first end it joins normally without an extension but at the other the arc continues on.
I have tried rebuilding the arc but it creates the same problem. I would guess it is down to how revit tries to join walls. 

I have tried to join the curves inside dynamo and then generate the walls from this prejoined line but the wall tool would accept the closed polycurve input.

Thanks, Siimon
'

title: b'Unable to edit code blocks on opening file'
body:
b'Ver:0.7.1.2999

In the latest daily build, I am unable to edit existing code blocks on opening a file.

It prevents me from tweaking any earlier code. The only code blocks I can edit are those that are created after opening the file.

For a little while I felt this was a good change as it prevented changes being made to code blocks that caused dynamo to crash. But quickly realized that it is extremely inconvenient.

Regards,
Vikram Subbaiah
'

title: b'Error Computing Collisions - ACIS Access Violation'
body:
b"A new fun thing started happening yesterday afternoon.  This same Python node, or copies of it (it changes) throw this error:

![dynamo 2014-08-06 issue](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2084232/3842818/8d150f92-1e3a-11e4-8a3a-ffd9597e1c28.png)

What do you make of this?  Debug -> ForceReExec does not fix it.  This node has a recursive function that making calls to the geometry library. My first suspicion was maybe it goes too deep but I put a counter in to track the maximum depth and the deepest dive is 250, which is a lot, but not too deep I think.  It is basically taking a surface, and a list of maybe 200 solids, and trying to subtract the solids from the surface.  It does this for a list of surfaces.

This same Python node has been in the definition for a while and it and the nodes leading into haven't changed.  What has changed is that I added a copy of this node in another part of the definition.  Now this error will usually occur in the new one, but sometime both.

Successive runs cause the memory being used to explode, and run times go way up.

Also,  is there a way to take solids out of this problem?  I really have two surfaces and I want to subtract from the first surface the second one along a given vector.  The only way I found was thickening the surface then calling subtract from.  
"

title: b'About full re-execution of Dynamo when liked to Revit'
body:
b'From the very first moment I have used 0.7 I have been surprised how smart worked the execution every time I click "run". Its was  processing ONLY the things that imply a change (new nodes, changes in the var). That means, for example, that after making a heavy processing of hundreds of solid operations:
--If I add a watch node to check a var and click run it is not processing again everything. It showed intermediately the var.
--If I make a list with some elements of the result of the process and add some nodes for export a sat file and click run, Dynamo is not processing again everything. Just the time for exporting (normally almost instantaneous)
-If I change something in the latest states of the process and click run. Dynamo is not processing again everything, just the last part of the process that is affected.
This smart behavior if the execution make working with heavy model quite fluid and convenient.

From some moment in the last weeks, when Dynamo is linked to Revit, every time that I click run it is making a full re-execution, if any part of the graphic is making "something" with Revit elements. Doesn't matter if I make any change or not. In all the previous examples it will make the full process again. Compared with the old behavior is really a dramatic difference when you work with heavy files.

I understand that there will be a reason for this full re-execution. But it makes Dynamo dramatically slower in real use. Please consider to come-back to the old behavior. Or at least let the users to select if they want full re-execution or not.Thanks. 
'

wish is to include a node that when executed, dirties the graph explicitly.

title: b'Issues with PolyCurves with fillet (they make Dynamo crash) '
body:
b'When making a coordinate system at parameter (or at distance) in polycurves with fillets, Dynamo is crashing (and Revit with it, if it is the case). 
![01](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6596042/3595224/8f7fd6e4-0cb1-11e4-9a96-8a937c77900a.jpg)
![02](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6596042/3595226/93313a58-0cb1-11e4-8827-48a193b72e1b.jpg)

You can find this sample here 
https://www.dropbox.com/s/fzj9tlg1bvnevw0/test.dyn

I have tried to remake the polycurve after the fillet operation, making the first and last segment as lines and joining again with the arc and everything seems to work normally..

After they polycurve by points operation (and after the fillet one), if you extract the curves,  the straight lines are listed as generic curves, not lines. So maybe this condition is being somehow problematic.

I have to test it more, but for example if you make a sweep using a path that is a PolyCurve by points, it would be slower that if you make the path making the straight lines and joining.
'

title: b"Dynamo won't open at all"
body:
b'Dynamo won't start.  I merged this morning into a branch that exactly matches your master.  I hit the Dynamo addin button, the wheel spins for a few seconds, then the button remains grayed out after control returns to Revit.  I can use Revit after this, but Dynamo button stays grayed out.  

To make sure I wasn't doing something to cause this, I installed Dynamo from your most recent Dynamo installer (DynamoInstall0.7.1.20140714T0722.exe).  This produced the same behavior.  

Sometime after calling "CreateDynamoRevitControllerAndViewModel" in DynamoRevit, the main thread runs out of things to do, and ProtoScript.Runners.LiveRunner.TaskExecMethod just runs over and over, sleeping for 10ms, waiting for a task.

This could be a red herring, but the two times I stepped through, the main thread makes it to "Dynamo.VisualizationManager" constructor before control suddenly returns to Revit, and the main thread in the threads window reads "unavailable" like it doesn't have any code left to execute.

This seems like some sort of threading issue.  Any help on this is greatly appreciated.  I was trying to get you guys something this morning on my other recently opened issue, but I have to get Dynamo running to do that.  

I observed this behavior last week, but upon restarting Revit the issue would go away, so this doesn't necessarily have anything to do with changes since last Thursday.
'

title: b'Dynamo becoming unusable, execution time grows exponentially'
body:
b"Upon starting Revit and Dynamo for the first time, the definition executes in a reasonable amount of time, but only the first two times it is executed.  The second execution is slightly faster, as I would expect.  The third execution is 60 times slower.  60.  

Here are screenshots of two separate sessions of Revit.  Each run is apples to apples, the the same input is changed each time, and in a way that produces roughly the same number of objects:

![dynamorevit 2014-07-11 time 02](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2084232/3555938/5476edfe-091d-11e4-9b11-107db1f88595.PNG)
![dynamorevit 2014-07-11 time](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2084232/3555939/57cf5e64-091d-11e4-85da-ab46e6177c9c.PNG)

Also, during the third execution, the physical memory usage goes way up.  Total memory usage was at 10gb up until hitting run the third time, and then goes to 11.7gb:
![dynamorevit 2014-07-11 memory](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2084232/3555966/da7bcfc8-091d-11e4-98e5-b156fcf2934f.PNG)

I will try to make an example that reproduces this, but it will take time.  If you are open to seeing the actual project file and definition I'm using that is ok with me, it is just a large project file.  This seems like a memory leak.

![dynamorevit 2014-07-11 memory 03](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2084232/3555994/7da33308-091e-11e4-8218-af25ca0b6acd.PNG)

I don't think I will be able to run a memory allocation profile successfully in this situation.  I thought that maybe it was something to do with IronPython, and it may be.  The only random, feeble dart I threw at it was to create a runtime for the script engine that can be shutdown after execution, just to try to make sure things are getting let go of.  This didn't do anything.  

The only python node that is getting executed on subsequent runs after the first one works with points, polycurves, and creates surfaces.  The return is an array of surfaces.

Any help will be greatly appreciated.
"

title: b'Auto-Layout - Should functions be aligned on the very left?'

b'I quite like the new auto-layout functionality. In a small definition (see screenshot) this may be okay, but in a larger definition it definitely looks funny and makes the graph hard to read. - Inputs
- Primitives
- Selects
- Nodes without inputs (e.g. Document)
- Code blocks (perhaps)

title: b'Revit evaporates when creating multiple instances of Geometry library objects in Python node'
body:
b"I have run into an issue with python nodes that contain classes.  What appears to be happening is that iteratively creating objects that use LibG results in Revit segfaulting, which is brutal when working in a big model.  When debugging it shows System.AccessViolationException.  Specifically I'm experiencing this with Surface.ByPerimeterPoints().  I'm not having any issues other than when creating instances in a loop, list comprehension, lambda expression etc.  

The link below is a link to a simple definition that reproduces the error.  There is a class that takes points. There is a method that creates calls Surface.ByPerimeterPoints.  This only happens when creating several instances of the class.  Creating one instance of the class and setting an attribute to a Geometry library object works as expected.  

It may have nothing to do with classes at all, and more to do with the creation of several instances of a type that is in the Geometry library, but this is similar to what the actual project I'm working on is doing.  If you move the creation of the surfaces out of the class method, I believe the same Revit evaporation will occur.  Here is a screenshot from debugging the actual project I first observed this on.  

To make sure it wasn't something I did while building, I installed your latest build from dynamobim.org, and the same thing happened.  

This is a major hang up for me right now.  Hopefully I'm an idiot and there is a simple explanation.  I've tried to make this easy for you guys to look at.  Please let me know I can provide additional information.
